[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Classical Slav"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Welcome to the Course"]
[Date "2023.03.06"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/22997200"]

1. { Hello and welcome to this Lifetime Repertoire about the Slav Defense!

One of the main criteria I have always had when studying openings is the idea of efficiency. We should always try to study smarter rather than more.

For this purpose, I really love the Slav Defense. Nowadays, some of the most popular openings against 1.d4 at the very top level include the Semi-Tarrasch and the Ragozin. Those are both excellent openings, of course, but when choosing to play either of them, one must also be ready for both the Nimzo-Indian and the Catalan. That, in fact, makes it three openings to learn rather than one.

That was one of the reasons why I have previously studied the ...a6 Queen's Gambit in detail, which resulted in my previous course - The Magnus Queen's Gambit. By playing 1...d5, 2...e6, 3...a6, one also skips the entire Nimzo & Catalan areas.

The Slav Defense does the same, and already on move 2, we are the ones that choose which opening it will be. This is, in my view, a great advantage of playing the Slav. Indeed, it turned out that this entire Lifetime Repertoire is still smaller than my Ruy Lopez course, despite it starting on move 3 and only covering one opening!

While this Lifetime Repertoire is certainly intended to work against very strong opposition, I believe it is also well-suited for lower-rated players. The number of theoretical lines one has to remember by heart is relatively low compared to other mainline openings. More importantly, many middlegames tend to revolve around the same structure, making it much easier to learn and understand.

My first Chessable course was about the Ruy Lopez, an opening I have played all my life with both colors. The Slav is slightly different. With White, I play everything, but more 1.e4 than 1.d4, and throughout my career, I have played very few games in the Slav as Black.

Around a year ago, I started to study the Slav more seriously from the Black side and incorporated it into my repertoire. Since then, I have analyzed, prepared, and played the Slav a lot, which has fundamentally changed my view of the opening! Previously, I considered the Slav a solid but somewhat passive opening, but when studying it more, I found out how beautifully strategically complex it is. In most of the lines, the battle is rich, with plenty of chances to outplay one's opponent while at the same time always being solid.

Another interesting thing that struck me was just how many of the typical ideas and structures reappear in the different lines, meaning that once we've understood how to handle a structure/maneuver/typical idea in one line, we are very likely to be able to use it in positions within our repertoire as well. This brings a big practical advantage, as we are much more likely to understand the middlegame better than our opponent.

Actually, it was only after experiencing these things for myself in practice that I suddenly realized that all those aspects make the Slav exceptionally well-suited for a course! I hope that I have managed to explain these ideas well in the course, and I would especially advise you to have a careful look at the Thematic Exercises [/course/140404/17] and Model Games [/course/140404/16] chapters.

Not having the same lifelong experience with the subject is a double-edged sword. There is some risk that I might have missed some forgotten lines due to my lack of practical experience, but another important factor is that I have been able to see the entire material with fresh eyes.

This might sound abstract, but I believe it's an important element. For instance, in the mainline of the Slow Slav, [/course/140404/6] I came across an idea [/variation/22637680/#/9/b] that was played only once in a position with many thousands of games! This would be much less likely to happen if I didn't have limited prior knowledge.

I hope you find the Slav as rich and enticing as I do and that you enjoy its study and practice thanks to this course! } -- {[%mdl 32768]} *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Classical Slav"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Repertoire Choices"]
[Date "2023.03.06"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/22997201"]
[ECO "D10"]

1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} d5 
2. c4 c6 { In this repertoire, I have tried as far as possible to keep us within the same structures and the same general developing schemes whenever possible. In general, White has two ways of dealing with the Slav:

1) In a concrete way, like the mainline with 6.Ne5, [/course/140404/2] the Geller Gambit, [/course/140404/4] the Meran Attempt, [/course/140404/7] and similar.

2) In a slow and solid way, like the Slow Slav, [/course/140404/6] 4.g3, 4.Nbd2 (both covered in this chapter [/course/140404/9]), or similar lines. } { Against approach 1, we have to know a little bit more concrete theory; that is especially true against @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp2pppp/2p2n2/5b2/P1pP4/2N2N2/1P2PPPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@ 6.Ne5 . Therefore, in the Morozevich Slav, [/course/140404/2] I have given two very different options in the critical juncture against 6.Ne5. One more solid, [/variation/22619881/#/16/b] trying to equalize concretely, and another slower, [/variation/22619884/#/16/b] where we try to get a rich game and outplay our opponents.

Approach 2 is, in my experience, way more common in practical play, probably because White does not want to bother with learning long lines against the Slav, as it is much rarer than the QGD/Nimzo/Catalan systems.

However, facing approach 2 is also easier for us. We don't really have to choose between a richer game or a more solid one, as we often are able to get both! Here it is especially important to focus on understanding the middlegames arising rather than the specific opening moves. Normally, I quite like to offer a few different alternatives for us here and there, but against the slower systems, I didn't really see the need, as I was usually happy with only one!

Another important part of the repertoire is White's alternatives to 2.c4, not allowing us to play the Slav. The most important alternative would, of course, be the London System. [/course/140404/12] The funny thing about this is that the London is an attempt to play the Slav with reversed colors! This should make us feel more comfortable here, and I have also tried to give a classical and easy-to-learn setup that works against all move orders.

As for the other moves, like the early alternatives [/course/140404/14] 3.g3 and 3.e3, things are actually rather simple. Generally speaking, those systems are aimed at fighting against the QGD/Nimzo/Catalan openings, whereas against our Slav setup, White usually has nothing better than, at some point, playing c4, transposing back to our Slav. } 
