[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Classical Slav"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Exchange #1"]
[Date "2023.03.06"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/23205842"]
[ECO "D10"]

1. d4 d5 
2. c4 c6 ( { The Slav! By playing the move ...c6, we support the d5-pawn, but the major difference to } 2...e6 { is that our light-squared bishop is not getting blocked in. Indeed, one of the main advantages of the Slav is that we rarely get bad pieces. Having played the Black side of the Queen's Gambit Declined and the Catalan, I have too many times experienced great suffering due to the c8-bishop never entering the game. That's one of the main reasons I was so happy incorporating the Slav in my Black Repertoire. } ) 
3. cxd5 {[%mdl 32768]} cxd5 { The Exchange Slav is one of White's most solid ways of facing the Slav. With the pawn structure in the center more static, it simply becomes more challenging to create imbalances.

However, we should not forget that there are still 30 pieces on the board, which means there are plenty of possibilities for both sides. As Black, one has to make an important choice of how ambitious and provocative one wants to play.

Finally, after much consideration, I decided to recommend what I believe to be the most solid and simple way of handling the Exchange Slav. The downside of my proposed repertoire is that it could, at times, become a little bit dry. } 
4. Nc3 { It is important to pay very close attention to White's possible move orders. There are many natural moves like Nc3, Nf3, Bf4, e3, and so on, but the order in which they are played makes some difference.

However, one of the main advantages of the system I recommend is that we are hard to trick move order-wise. We can usually play the same moves no matter what White does. } Nf6 
5. Bf4 { By far, the mainline. By delaying Nf3, White makes it a bit trickier for us to develop our light-squared bishop. } Nc6 
6. e3 ( 6.Nf3 a6 { transposes here. [/variation/22642539/#/6/b] } ) a6 { Again, I recommend the multi-purpose move ...a6. It stops Bb5, but, more importantly, it prepares the development of our light-squared bishop. As soon as the bishop develops, Qb3 is an important reply. With the pawn already on a6, we can safely meet it by ...Na5 Qa4+ b5. } 
7. Bd3 { This is an important and popular move I faced recently against German GM Nisipeanu. I have also tried this setup myself as White. The point is to delay Nf3 in order to put a pawn there later on. } Bg4 { Against 7.Rc1 [/variation/22642546/#/7/w] we did not like to put our bishop here, as it would come under attack by the white kingside pawns. With the bishop already on d3, this is not an issue, as we will be able to trade the bishops off. } 
8. Nge2 { Overwhelmingly most popular. } e6 {[%cal Gf8d6,Ge8g8]} 
9. O-O Bd6 ( { Keeping more pieces with } 9...Be7!? { is also possible, but this looks straightforward for Black. We are not afraid of trades and simply develop our pieces to natural squares. } ) 
10. f3 { The most critical move. White loses no time and tries to establish a knight on c5 as quickly as possible. } Bh5 
11. Na4 ( { Basically the only strategic idea available to White. } 11.Rc1 Bxf4 12.Nxf4 Bg6 13.Na4 Nd7 { led to a very instructive victory for Black in Barbot-Kasimdzhanov. [/variation/22768397/#/11/w] } ) O-O 
12. Nc5 Bxc5 { Not strictly necessary, but now that White has to recapture with the d-pawn, I believe this gives us plenty of counterplay. } 
13. dxc5 Bg6 {[%cal Gf8e8,Gf6d7]} { Remember this! Not so much the move itself, but the fact that we refrain from pushing ...e5. It might look natural to advance in the center, but here it will mainly create weaknesses, so we should keep our structure intact for the time being. } 
14. Bd6 Re8 {[%cal Gf6d7,Gb7b6]} { I believe we have zero worries here. One of the things working in our favor is that White's most natural plan, pushing a3 and b4, gives us an excellent square for a knight on c4. If White doesn't push these pawns, then we can break out with ...b6. Eventually, our extra central pawn will compensate for White’s extra bishop. } 
