1. d4 d5 
2. c4 c6 ( { The Slav! By playing the move ...c6, we support the d5-pawn, but the major difference to } 2...e6 { is that our light-squared bishop is not getting blocked in. Indeed, one of the main advantages of the Slav is that we rarely get bad pieces. Having played the Black side of the Queen's Gambit Declined and the Catalan, I have too many times experienced great suffering due to the c8-bishop never entering the game. That's one of the main reasons I was so happy incorporating the Slav in my Black Repertoire. } ) 
3. Nf3 ( { If White intends to develop both knights on moves 3 and 4, they usually start with } 3.Nf3 { but, from our perspective, it doesn't really matter, as we reply in the same way. } ) Nf6 { The most natural developing move. Now a lot depends on White's next move. If White is in an ambitious mood, they will try to prevent us from developing our light-squared bishop on the next move. If they are more solidly inclined, they allow it, and a slightly slower game emerges. } 
4. e3 { The so-called Slow Slav. A seemingly modest move, but I would argue it's even the single most critical line against the Slav on higher levels nowadays.

The reason is, as so often in modern chess, that the somewhat less forcing nature of the position makes it harder for Black players to 'kill' the game by making it too forcing. This does not bother us, however, as we are more than happy to get an interesting fight with lots of play for both sides! } Bf5 {[%cal Ge7e6][%csl Yf5]} { As a rule of thumb, when we can, we should always develop our bishop outside the pawn chain. When doing so, we must always be careful about our weakened queenside. Especially the move Qb3 should be kept in mind, as the b7-pawn lacks support. Here, due to White's somewhat slow move 4.e3, this is not really an issue. }
5. Nc3 ( { At this point, } 5.Qb3 { is not dangerous at all. We can go } 5...Qc7 { as, due to White having played e3 already, we never have to worry about Bf4. Now } 6.cxd5 cxd5 { would transpose here. [/variation/22637662/#/6/b] } ) e6 
6. Nh4 ( { Now something like } 6.Be2 { is too slow! } 6...h6 { Saving our f5-bishop. These positions are really comfortable for Black, as White lacks a clear plan, whereas we will complete our development with ...Nbd7, ...Bd6, and ...O-O. Our bishop will retreat to h7 if needed. } ) { Basically the only challenging move. } Be4 ( { Upping the stakes a bit. In order to win our bishop, White now has to play f3. That could be a useful extra tempo for pushing in the center, but it is also a weakness that makes it a whole lot less tempting to castle kingside. In short, the game simply gets a bit more double-edged.

Historically, } 6...Bg6 { has been the most common move. There is no doubt that it's solid, but even less doubt that it's also solid for White! Usually, a long game emerges where White is a tiny bit better with the bishop pair. I never liked openings in which we are only trying to equalize, and therefore the } ) ( 6...Bg6 { line never really interested me a whole lot from Black's point of view. } ) 
7. f3 ( 7.Qb3 { Similar to the previous move,  [/variation/22637664/#/6/w] this is again a slightly dubious move order. } 7...Qb6 { Utilizing the same tactical trick. } 8.f3?! Qxb3 9.axb3 Bc2 { picks up the b3-pawn. } ) Bg6 { The starting position of the line. Strategically speaking, the position is an interesting one. White will win the bishop pair, but the dark squares are weakened with the ugly f3-move. Still, this is not that simple to utilize, and for the time being, our pieces are rather passive. There are many different move orders and ways for White to play, which is typical for such not so forcing openings.

Still, it makes sense to go into some detail about how exactly we are handling White's different attempts, and I would advise you to take your time and carefully figure out the differences between the different White options over the next 3-4 moves. }
8. Qb3 ( { Generally speaking, } 8.Nxg6 { is not the most accurate move. While it's true that one of White's main ideas is to win the bishop pair, there is no reason to take just yet, as our bishop is anyway not going anywhere. Most likely, this transposes to some of the other lines after } 8...hxg6 { . } ) { This is the main move. White puts some pressure but, most importantly, forces us to make an important choice. } Qc7 ( { The more interesting option, keeping the queens on the board. } 8...Qb6 { is perfectly possible, but I don't like it too much. It is reminiscent of @@StartFEN@@rn1qkb1r/pp3ppp/2p1pn2/3p1b2/2PP3N/2N1P3/PP3PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@ 6...Bg6 in that it's much more solid for both sides but also gives a lot less potential for grabbing the initiative later on. I'd again like to stress that this has nothing to do with any objective evaluation between the options but is purely my stylistic choice. } ) 
9. Bd2 {[%mdl 32768]} { The most straightforward and logical move, and the move I faced last time I had this position as Black. White develops the bishop and prepares to either castle long or bring the rook to c1. } a5 { Highly controversial! From the thousands of games that reached this position, this move was only played twice. One of which was by myself...

The concept is a rather new one. Previously, Black's main source of counterplay was connected to the idea of ...dxc4 followed by ...a6, ...b5, and finally ...c5. This is still certainly a good plan, but it does allow White time to get their king into relative safety in the meantime. } 
10. cxd5 { The best move, highlighting the main downside of ...a5 - we can't take with the c-pawn any longer, as it would leave the b5-square way too weak. } Nxd5 { Important! It's in our interest to trade another set of knights, as we are fighting against the bishop pair. Additionally, without the knight on c3 we get the possibility of ...Bb4, trading bishops later on. } 
11. e4 { Definitely the most natural move, and again clearly highlighting our previous move's downside of our previous move. White grabs the center, but this is not exclusively a good thing because it also gives us some targets and extra potential for counterplay. } Nxc3 { Further strengthening White's center, but again this is not the end of the world. } 
12. bxc3 b5 { This move symbolizes an integral part of our strategy, and now is a good time to think more about the position in general. At a very superficial glance, it looks like White is much better. They have the center, and will, at any point, gain the bishop pair.

However, fascinatingly enough, it's tough to make anything of these two advantages. Somehow, the center is not very mobile, and it's not so easy to say where White should try to play.

The most natural way is probably to ruin our queenside structure by pushing a4, but as we shall see, this also does not turn out so well for White. We'd get a passed a-pawn and play on the b-file while White gets... nothing? } 
13. Nxg6 { Perhaps not strictly necessary, but we are anyway likely to play ...Be7 next, forcing it. } hxg6 
14. a4 { As mentioned, this is natural, but not working out so well. } bxa4! {[%csl Ga5]} { This is always our reaction here. The a-pawn is surprisingly potent, and once it reaches a3, it's hard for White to attack it. } 
15. Qxa4 Nd7 {[%cal Gd7b6,Ga5a4,Ga4a3]} { Followed by ...Nb6 and ...a5-...a4-...a3. } ( { This is a more accurate move order than } 15...Be7 { . Check the game Plazuelo Pascual-Alsina Leal [/variation/22768394] for details. } ) 
