1. d4 d5 
2. c4 c6 ( { The Slav! By playing the move ...c6, we support the d5-pawn, but the major difference to } 2...e6 { is that our light-squared bishop is not getting blocked in. Indeed, one of the main advantages of the Slav is that we rarely get bad pieces. Having played the Black side of the Queen's Gambit Declined and the Catalan, I have too many times experienced great suffering due to the c8-bishop never entering the game. That's one of the main reasons I was so happy incorporating the Slav in my Black Repertoire. } ) 
3. Nf3 ( { If White intends to develop both knights on moves 3 and 4, they usually start with } 3.Nf3 { but, from our perspective, it doesn't really matter, as we reply in the same way. } ) Nf6 { The most natural developing move. Now a lot depends on White's next move. If White is in an ambitious mood, they will try to prevent us from developing our light-squared bishop on the next move. If they are more solidly inclined, they allow it, and a slightly slower game emerges. } 
4. g3 {[%mdl 32768]} Bf5 ( { The Fianchetto Variation is a popular try for White, mainly because of its simplicity - it can be played against the King's Indian and Grünfeld as well as being combined with the Catalan. For instance, Srinath Narayanan does precisely that in his Catalan LTR on Chessable. Indeed, should you have the Grünfeld on your repertoire, then } 4...g6 { is an excellent move that I have played many times myself. However, sticking to the pure Slav is also perfectly possible, even in various ways. } ) ( 4...dxc4 { is the most ambitious move, trying to hold onto the pawn, but it's not quite the same without White having committed their knight to c3. Putting the bishop on g4 instead of f5 is also perfectly playable, but in the end, I decided that } ) ( 4...Bf5 { is the move that goes best together with the rest of our repertoire. } ) 
5. Nc3 e6 ( 5...h6 { is a bit too slow due to } 6.cxd5 cxd5 7.Qb3 { when both d5 and b7 are weak. } ) 
6. Qb3 { Srinath Narayanan's recommendation in his LTR on the Catalan. } Qb6 ( { Again, this is necessary, as } 6...Qc7 { runs into } 7.Bf4 { . } ) 
7. c5 { Necessary sooner or later, as otherwise we trade on b3 and win the pawn by ... Bc2! } Qxb3 
8. axb3 Be7 {[%cal Ye6e5,Gc6b5,Rb3b4,Rb4b5]} ( { Natural development. It's possible to go for more forcing play with } 8...Na6 { intending } 9.-- { ...Bc2 picking up the b3-pawn, but White gets a lot of initiative by sacrificing it. Therefore, I recommend just developing naturally instead. However, it's important to know about the ideas here, as we otherwise risk drifting into a worse position rather easily.

White intends to push b4-b5 at some point, and we will struggle to stop it in a good way. Instead, we should be ready to take cxb5 and open up the c-file before White can stabilize completely. If White delays b4-b5, our main plan is to prepare the ...e5-break, getting counterplay in the center. } ) 
9. Bf4 Nbd7 { Continuing with our development. If White pushes b4-b5, the knight would prefer to stay on b8, but I am not too concerned about the b5-push anyway, as it gives us some quick counterplay on the queenside. } 
10. b4 { Definitely the most natural move. This is White's big strategic idea. Srinath Narayanan ends here in his nice LTR Catalan. } h6 {[%cal Rf3h4,Gg7g5]} { A nice little move that is almost always useful. Apart from preventing Nh4, it also prepares to push ...g5, which would release White's pressure on the e5-square. } 
11. b5 g5 { Kicking the bishop away. } 
12. Bd2 { Actually, all squares are possible, and it's hard to say which one is stronger. } cxb5 {[%cal Gf6e4,Yb7b6]} { An important strategic idea! Structurally, it looks a bit odd for Black, but we get a surprising amount of counterplay along the c-file. Our ideas include ...Ne4 followed by pushing ...b6 later on. } 
13. Nxb5 O-O { If White got a couple of moves, they would get a nice edge, but our counterplay is fast. } 
14. Bg2 a6 
15. Nc3 Rfc8 {[%cal Gb7b6,Ga6a5,Rc5c6][%csl Rc5]} { Intending ...b6, or even ...a5 followed by ...b6. } 
16. b4 Ne4 {[%cal Ge7f6,Gb7b6,Ga6a5][%csl Rd4]} { After ...Bf6 next, all our pieces are active. We have the ...b6 and ...a5 ideas, but the pawn on d4 is also a bit soft. Most likely, the pawns on b4 and c5 will get traded off, which leaves White with nothing to hope for long term. } 
