[Date "2023.03.06"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/23205840"]
[ECO "D11"]

1. d4 d5 
2. c4 c6 ( { The Slav! By playing the move ...c6, we support the d5-pawn, but the major difference to } 2...e6 { is that our light-squared bishop is not getting blocked in. Indeed, one of the main advantages of the Slav is that we rarely get bad pieces. Having played the Black side of the Queen's Gambit Declined and the Catalan, I have too many times experienced great suffering due to the c8-bishop never entering the game. That's one of the main reasons I was so happy incorporating the Slav in my Black Repertoire. } ) 
3. Nf3 ( { If White intends to develop both knights on moves 3 and 4, they usually start with } 3.Nf3 { but, from our perspective, it doesn't really matter, as we reply in the same way. } ) Nf6 { The most natural developing move. Now a lot depends on White's next move. If White is in an ambitious mood, they will try to prevent us from developing our light-squared bishop on the next move. If they are more solidly inclined, they allow it, and a slightly slower game emerges. } 
4. Qb3 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { The } 4.Qb3 { system has always been popular for White but never the mainline. Stylistically, it's a solid way to play, but not without venom. White is making sure they can develop their pieces and get castled, and they prefer to play a middlegame with most pieces on the board.

This sort of approach should not bother us, as we are generally looking for a game, but it's useful to be aware of how to handle it, as otherwise, it's easy to drift into positions that are very easy for White to play. } ) dxc4 { Just as in the normal Slav lines, we give up the center to get easy development for our pieces. } 
5. Qxc4 Bf5 ( { The traditional mainline. For a while, } 5...Bg4 { was topical, and it still seems like a decent alternative, but I see no reason not to stick to our usual development scheme with the bishop on f5. Next up, we intend to calmly complete our development while making sure that White is never able to push e4. } { This position can also be reached via the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pppp/2p2n2/3p4/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Qc2 dxc4 5.Qxc4 Bf5 move order. } ) 
6. g3 { This is the most common move and, basically, the only one currently played. It might look like one of many reasonable ways to develop, but it is, in fact, clearly the most logical.

The point is that developing the dark-squared bishop will leave it vulnerable to either attacks (on f4, with ... Nd5 or ...Nh5) or trades (on g5, after we play ...Be7). } ( { As White has a space advantage (as ever in the Slav, due to our ...dxc4), they, in principle, try to keep as many pieces on the board. Therefore, the choice is between } 6.e3 { and } ) ( 6.g3 { , but } ) ( 6.e3 { would block in the bishop on c1. Therefore, only } ) ( 6.g3 { remains. } ) e6 { Play now resembles the Catalan a bit, but as usual in the Slav, the main difference is that our light-squared bishop is outside the pawn chain, which wouldn't be the case in the Catalan. That means this is strategically less dangerous for Black.

Another important and interesting aspect is that, unlike in the Catalan, we have no rush to push ...e5 or ...c5 to get out, as our pieces will find decent squares anyway. In fact, pushing ...e5, and especially ...c5, is more likely leading to White's g2-bishop becoming stronger, whereas with our pawn still on c6 that bishop is somewhat blocked. } 
7. Bg2 Be7 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gb8a6,Ga6b4][%csl Ge7]} { In general, the nature of the position is rather slow; therefore, concrete theory isn't very important, but it's still useful to be familiar with a couple of ideas. The first small point has to do with move orders. We play ...Be7 before ...Nbd7 as it's more flexible. The bishop always belongs to e7, whereas the knight can sometimes be useful also via a6-b4. } 
8. O-O O-O { Now White has tried many different moves and plans. Again, this is not the most theoretically challenging area, so keep an extra focus on understanding the general ideas. } 
9. Nc3 {[%cal Gf1e1,Ge2e4]} { This is White's most direct way of playing. They intend Re1 to push e4 immediately. } Nbd7 { Now, there is no reason to refrain from our most natural developing move. } 
10. Re1 { The only logical follow-up to the previous move. } Bg6!? ( { Slightly rare. By far, the most common move is } 10...Ne4 { , but it turns out that e4 isn't that big of a threat! } ) 
11. e4 Rc8!? {[%cal Gb7b5,Yc6c5]} ( { Defending c6 in order to play ...b5 on the next move. Actually, even the immediate } 11...b5 { is possible and sharper, but } ) ( 11...Rc8 { looks a bit simpler to me. } ) 
12. Qb3 Qb6 {[%cal Ga7b6,Gf8d8]} { This looks absolutely fine to me. White managed to get the e4-d4 center, but they are not really moving anyway, and we are not lacking space. Next up, we can even try to attack the pawns, hoping to provoke e5. The only thing to watch out for is the d5-break, but that should be easy enough to prevent. }
13.-- ( { Play may continue } 13.Qxb6 axb6 { Generally, the capture we want, as the d7-knight does a good job preventing Ne5, and the a-file can be a source of counterplay later on. Apart from the obvious ...Rfd8, we could now also consider ideas like ...b5-b4. } 14.Nh4 Bh5 { Keeping the bishop makes a lot of sense, as it controls the d1-square, making it easier for us to put pressure on the d4-pawn in the future. } 15.h3 { Intending to trap our bishop. I don’t really see any other reasonable ideas for White. } 15...Rfd8 16.g4 Ne8! { Hitting the h4-knight - an important idea that we have seen in other Slav lines. } 17.Nf3 Bg6 { . We have saved our bishop and can now look forward to our usual counterplay pushing our b-pawn, or perhaps even ...Bb4 followed by an attack on the e4-pawn. White has the center, but as we have good squares for all our pieces and clear ideas for counterplay, this does not bother us much. } )
