10. Ne4 { So we forced White's knight to e4 with tempo, but the problem for White is that it is the wrong knight! The f3-knight is in the way, as White would like to bring their queen over to h5 or g4. Therefore, White will find it hard to create serious threats here. } Be7 
11. Bg5 { A logical move, but allowing a knight to d6 is certainly not the end of the world for us. } O-O 
12. Bxe7 Qxe7 {[%cal Ga7a5,Yc4c3,Gc8a6]} { This looks fine for us. As soon as the knight leaves e4, we are ready to push ...c3, keeping our c-pawn alive. } 
13. Re1 {[%cal Gf3d2,Gd2c4,Gc4d6]} { Sipke Ernst's recommendation in his 'Seriously Shock the Semi-Slav'. The idea is to reroute the f3-knight via d2 to c4-d6. } a5 { In my view, the most logical and ambitious move! The bishop will find itself much safer on a6 with the pawn already on a5. } ( 13...c3 { is usually the more solid reply. We intend to give back the c-pawn in order to free ourselves and equalize the game. } 14.bxc3 bxc3 15.Qc1 { White has other moves as well, but none that really alters the character of the position. } 15...Bb7 16.Nxc3 Nxc3 17.Qxc3 c5 { White is optically a touch more active, but without weaknesses it should basically just be equal. } ) 
14. Rc1 {[%cal Rc4c3][%csl Rc4]} { The most solid move, simply aiming to pick up the c-pawn while stopping our ...c3-push. } Ba6 
15. Nfd2 N7b6 {[%cal Rd2c4]} { It's important not to allow the knight to c4! } 
16. Bf1 c3! { A recurring strategic idea in this line, but here it works even better as the light-squared bishops get traded off. } 
17. bxc3 Bxf1 
18. Kxf1 bxc3 
19. Nxc3 Rfd8 {[%csl Gd5]} { We have excellent counterplay. Most probably, the d4-pawn will get traded for the one on c6. Long term, perhaps White's king can be a little bit airy, while we have a strong outpost on d5 for a knight or a rook. } 
