11. Nxg6 hxg6 
12. Rd1 { The only move that is currently played at the top level. The rook is simply necessary on d1 to support e3-e4 later. Additionally, it allows tucking away the dark-squared bishop via d2 to e1, where it will not get traded. } ( 12.e4 { is premature due to } 12...Nb6 { hitting both c4 and d4 and actually winning a pawn immediately. } ) Qc7 { We had three possible squares for the queen - a5, e7, and c7. The a5-square is the most popular and arguably the most concrete, while I went to e7 myself in a recent game. To be honest, I believe they are all rather equal in strength, and I struggled to choose which one. On the other hand, if they are all good, then we also can't make a bad choice! } ( { The most natural square is arguably e7, and we often place our queen there, but on c7, it still controls the a5-square, making sure White can't fight back on the dark squares on the queenside. Additionally, } 12...Qc7 { was recently played by both Alireza Firouzja and Fabiano Caruana, which should count for something... } ) 
