17. Bg5 ( { A natural developing move. } 17.Nb5 { is a forcing approach advocated by the engines. } 17...Qe7 18.d6 { This is a surprising tactical idea. Otherwise, we would happily play ...Nd6 next. } 18...Nxd6 19.Nxd6 Bxd6 20.Qd3 { The point. Both d6 and g6 are hanging, so White wins back the pawn. } 20...Rfd8 21.Qxg6 Kf8 { Important, as we need to step out of the b3-g8 pin. White has traded a passed pawn for a doubled one, but it is still strategically a good trade for White as the b3-bishop becomes much stronger. } 22.Qf5 e4 { The last key move. Now we are ready to play ...Qe5 next, trading queens, after which the ending is just fine. } ) ( { Objectively speaking, the position after } 17.Bg5 { is fine for sure, and practically speaking, my feeling is that Black has very easy play with lots of active moves and good squares for all their pieces, while White’s d5-pawn will never, ever move. My main recommendation involves a pawn sacrifice - since I understand that some players might not like to be down material without any way of winning it back in the near future, I offer } 17...Qb6 { as an alternative. [/variation/23189259/#/17/b] } ) Nd6!? { Not necessary, but highly interesting! We are actually happy even to give up the e5-pawn to establish a grip on the dark squares. } 
18. Qxe5 Rfe8 
19. Qg3 Nfe4 { Trading off one of the few pieces potentially able to fight against our d6-blockade. } 
20. Nxe4 Rxe4 { I believe we have excellent compensation. White has an extra passed pawn and the bishop pair, but it's very hard to ever get it going. Meanwhile, we have ideas of ...Re2, after which both f2 and b2 are hanging. The queen will be excellently placed on b6, putting pressure on b3/b2 and the f2-pawn. } 
