[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Classical Slav"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Jobava London #1"]
[Date "2023.03.06"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/23205847"]
[ECO "D00"]

1. d4 d5 
2. Nc3 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf6 
3. Bf4 { The Jobava London! When Baadur Jobava started to play like this many years ago, people generally struggled to take it seriously. Normally, we are taught to not develop our knights in front of our pawns, but it has turned out to be quite venomous in practical play. } c5 ( { For this course, I have chosen a classical approach. In my previous course on the Magnus Queen's Gambit, I chose to recommend a system with ...Bf5. I still definitely believe this is a great system for Black, but in regards to the rest of our repertoire, and especially our setup against the London,  [/course/140404/12] I believe the mainline and classical approach with } 3...c5 { makes the most sense. } ) 
4. e3 { The main move, and the way both Jobava and Carlsen play. } cxd4 { In the London System chapter, I'll talk [/variation/22642673/#/7/b] a lot about how we were not so keen on entering the Carlsbad structure. With the knight on c3, things are a bit different, however. First of all, the knight is misplaced on c3 in the Carlsbad, as White prefers their pawn to support the center. Secondly, if we don't trade on d4, White can consider dxc5!? which makes it harder to regain the pawn due to the knight on c3 available to protect it. } 
5. exd4 Bg4!? ( 5...a6 { is the traditional move, and a solid one as well. It looks to me like it equalizes without any big effort, but I still prefer } ) ( 5...Bg4 { for its surprise value and the fact that we immediately put a little bit more pressure on White. } ) 
6. Be2 ( { Somewhat rare, but I believe it's at least as critical as the more common } 6.f3 { . Normally, the trade of bishops is beneficial for Black, but here White gains some time. } ) Bxe2 
7. Qxe2 a6 ( { A sad necessity - White was threatening Nb5. } 7...Nc6 8.Nb5 Rc8 9.Nd6+! { might be easy to miss in a game! } ) 
8. g4 { This looks like madman play, but in fact, it's highly logical. If White were to continue in slow fashion, we would simply emerge with a great Carlsbad, so White tries to use their lead in development. } Nc6 { Slightly controversial. In all games I could find, Black played ...h6 to stop White's pawn push. But I still wish for us to castle short, and then the h6-pawn is a pretty serious weakness. } 
9. g5 { Definitely, the reason everybody plays ...h6 as Black. } Ne4! { This is the point! It turns out that the tactics all work for us. } 
10. Nxe4 Nxd4! ( 10...dxe4 { is also interesting, but this strikes me as simpler. } ) 
11. Qd3 ( 11.Nd6+ Qxd6 12.Bxd6 Nxe2 13.Nxe2 exd6 { looks like an equal ending. White will win back the d5-pawn, but we will play ...h6 and generate counterplay against the g5-pawn. } ) dxe4 
12. Qxe4 { Material equality is restored, but we need to be a bit careful to stop White from O-O-O. } Qa5+ 
13. c3 ( 13.Bd2 Qa4! 14.b3 Qc6 { is a great ending for us, as the g5-pawn will get weak. } ) Nc6 { Now White can't castle long, as the a2-pawn would be hanging. } 
14. Nf3 Rd8 {[%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7,Ye7e6][%csl Rg5]} { Activating the rook, making ...Qd5 a possibility later on. Next up, we can finish our development on the kingside with either ...e6 or, perhaps preferably, ...g6. In the long run, White might regret having pushed the pawn all the way to g5... } 
