1. d4 d5 
2. Nc3 Nf6 
3. Bf4 { The Jobava London! When Baadur Jobava started to play like this many years ago, people generally struggled to take it seriously. Normally, we are taught to not develop our knights in front of our pawns, but it has turned out to be quite venomous in practical play. } c5 ( { For this course, I have chosen a classical approach. In my previous course on the Magnus Queen's Gambit, I chose to recommend a system with ...Bf5. I still definitely believe this is a great system for Black, but in regards to the rest of our repertoire, and especially our setup against the London,  [/course/140404/12] I believe the mainline and classical approach with } 3...c5 { makes the most sense. } ) 
4. e3 { The main move, and the way both Jobava and Carlsen play. } cxd4 { In the London System chapter, I talked [/variation/22642673/#/7/b] a lot about how we were not so keen on entering the Carlsbad structure. With the knight on c3, things are a bit different, however. First of all, the knight is misplaced on c3 in the Carlsbad, as White prefers their pawn to support the center. Secondly, if we don't trade on d4, White can consider dxc5!? which makes it harder to regain the pawn due to the knight on c3 available to protect it. } 
5. exd4 Bg4!? ( 5...a6 { is the traditional move, and a solid one as well. It looks to me like it equalizes without any big effort, but I still prefer } ) ( 5...Bg4 { for its surprise value and the fact that we immediately put a little bit more pressure on White. } ) 
6. f3 {[%mdl 32768]} { The most common move. Our bishop does not have a great square to retreat to, but on the other hand, White can no longer play Nf3. } Bd7 { Necessary, to cover the b5-square. The bishop is slightly clumsy here, but the pawn also looks really ugly on f3. } 
7. Bd3 { The most common move in practical play and the favorite of Jobava himself. The computers hate such play for White, but we should not underestimate it, as it's easy to drift into an unpleasant position. } Nc6 
8. Nge2 Nb4! {[%cal Gb4d3]} { A good move. The d3-bishop is clearly White's best piece, so we make sure to trade it off. We will be slightly behind in development, but White has no way of opening up the position quickly. } 
9. a3 { Forcing the issue, enabling White to castle long soon. } Nxd3+ 
10. Qxd3 e6 
11. O-O-O ( { This was played in Jobava-Navara, 2021. In these positions, it's important not to rush and simply have faith in the solidity of our position. } 11.h4 { was played in the correspondence game Nemec-Piaggesi, 2022. Again, we continue in the same calm way. } 11...Be7 12.h5 Rc8 { Castling immediately is also possible. } 13.h6 g6 { The dark squares are now slightly weakened, but on the other hand, White struggles to open up our king's position. } 14.Bg5 O-O 15.g4 Ne8! { A recurring good rerouting. Black was already slightly better, and indeed, went on to win a good game. } ) Be7 { Calmly preparing to castle. The remaining moves indicate how the game might develop rather than a concrete forcing line. } 
12. g4 { The most natural way of attacking. } O-O 
13. h4 Ne8! {[%cal Gb7b5,Gb5b4,Ge8d6,Gd6c4,Yd6f5]} { Remember this maneuver! White will anyway kick our knight away, so we might as well immediately reroute it. From d6 it can either go to f5, helping with the defense, or to c4, where it might create annoying threats toward the White king. Next up, ...b5-b4 is a dangerous idea to get counterplay. } 
