[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Classical Slav"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "London #1"]
[Date "2023.03.06"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/23205845"]
[ECO "D02"]

1. d4 d5 
2. Nf3 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf6 
3. Bf4 { The London system is a popular opening at all levels, and I believe for good reason. White can easily develop their pieces to sensible squares without having to worry about knowing too much theory.

Luckily, though, chess is a rich enough game for such a simplistic approach not to work every time. There are a couple of approaches to handling the London system as Black. One is to go for a very move-by-move-based strategy, trying to hinder White from developing normally. The other main approach is to choose a setup one is comfortable with, and just let both sides develop their pieces and refer the main fight to the middlegame.

In accordance with the classical style of this LTR, I have chosen the second option. } c5 { The main move and the most logical one. Since White puts no pressure on our d5-pawn, we can immediately grab more space. Our general setup now is ...Nc6, ...Bg4, ...e6, ...Be7, and ...O-O. If we get that far, we will have nothing at all to worry about.

White's main ways to disturb our setup are either to attack our bishop on g4, often hunting it down with a knight, or to put pressure on our queenside once the bishop is locked on the kingside.

In my previous course, 'The Magnus Queen's Gambit', I proposed a setup based on ...e6 and ...Bd6. While I still believe that setup is excellent, it clearly fits much better with the Queen's Gambit than with the Slav. } 
4. e3 { By far, the most common move. White keeps the c-pawn flexible, allowing both c4 in one move and Nc3 in some moments. } Nc6 { Continuing with our usual development scheme. } 
5. Nbd2 Bg4 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gf8e7,Ge8g8]} { This is our setup. The upside is developing the bishop outside the pawn chain so it will never get locked in. Also, the pin of the f3-knight makes c4 less tempting for White, as then we would have excellent pressure against the d4-pawn.

The big downside of ...Bg4 is that the bishop can easily get harassed by some combination of h3/g4/Nh4. However, from the Slav chapters, we got familiarized with the idea of giving it up for a knight already, so it should make us less nervous here. } 
6. h3 { This is tricky! By not committing the pawn to c3 yet, White is ready for concrete play in case we are not careful. I consider this a decent try for White, and it was the recommendation offered by Srinath Narayanan and Sahaj Grover in their excellent LTR London Repertoire. } Bxf3 { Definitely the most solid move. } 
7. Nxf3 e6 {[%cal Gf8d6]} { We have given up the bishop pair, but don't despair. We gave up the light-squared bishop regularly in both the Slow Slav [/course/140404/6] and, particularly, the Exchange Slav, [/course/140404/11] and just like there, that is based on the solidness of our position.

We have zero weaknesses, good control over the center, and easy development. White will also struggle to keep their dark-squared bishop alive, as we intend to trade it next with ...Bd6. } 
8. Be2 { This move order was suggested by Srinath and Sahaj, and it makes a lot of sense. } Bd6 
9. dxc5 { Again, other moves would let us trade bishops and equalize immediately. } Bxf4!? ( 9...Bxc5 { is possible here as well, but White will push c4 in one go, and this gives them a very slight initiative. } ) 
10. exf4 { This structure is something we should be familiar with. If you see it for the first time, you might think White is worse due to the doubled pawns and the recapture away from the center, but in reality, the structure makes a lot of sense for White. The semi-open e- and d-files combine nicely with the outpost on e5.

The good thing for us here is that we have gotten rid of our light-squared bishop, which is usually our most problematic piece in this structure. } Ne4 { An interesting touch that, objectively, doesn't change anything, but I believe it makes it easier to play as Black. We are recapturing the c5-pawn with the knight instead of the queen (with ...Qa5+), and the reason is that White's most normal setup would involve moving the bishop to d3, opening up the e-file, and aiming at our kingside. We anticipate that plan and get ready to simply capture the bishop once it gets there! } 
11. O-O Nxc5 {[%cal Ye2d3,Rc5d3,Yd8f6,Rf6f4,Rf6b2,Ge8g8]} 
12. c3 { The most natural move. First of all, the pawn usually goes to c3 in the London, and here specifically, it allows White to cover both pawns on b2 and f4 with Qd2 in case we play ...Qf6 later on. } O-O { The problem for White is that, in the long run, it's very hard to get by without Bd3, but trading the bishop for our knight would eliminate one of White's main long-term assets. } 
13. Bd3 ( { Perhaps something like } 13.Qc2 { makes sense, but as mentioned, it's hard for White to get by without Bd3 in the long run, anyway. } 13...Qb6 { intending to bring the rooks to d8 and c8 looks perfectly healthy. } ) Qb6 { Useful to flick in, especially now that White's queen already has to defend d3. } 
14. Rb1 Nxd3 { Not strictly necessary. Placing a rook on d8 is also fine, but it makes sense to trade immediately for simplicity's sake. } 
15. Qxd3 Rad8 {[%cal Gh7h6,Yd5d4]} { Intending to push ...d4 at a later moment, if allowed. But mainly, we have removed a lot of White's attacking potential, and without weaknesses, we have nothing to worry about. } 
