3. Bf4 { The London system is a popular opening at all levels, and I believe for good reason. White can easily develop their pieces to sensible squares without having to worry about knowing too much theory.

Luckily, though, chess is a rich enough game for such a simplistic approach not to work every time. There are a couple of approaches to handling the London system as Black. One is to go for a very move-by-move-based strategy, trying to hinder White from developing normally. The other main approach is to choose a setup one is comfortable with, and just let both sides develop their pieces and refer the main fight to the middlegame.

In accordance with the classical style of this LTR, I have chosen the second option. } c5 { The main move and the most logical one. Since White puts no pressure on our d5-pawn, we can immediately grab more space. Our general setup now is ...Nc6, ...Bg4, ...e6, ...Be7, and ...O-O. If we get that far, we will have nothing at all to worry about.

White's main ways to disturb our setup are either to attack our bishop on g4, often hunting it down with a knight, or to put pressure on our queenside once the bishop is locked on the kingside.

In my previous course, 'The Magnus Queen's Gambit', I proposed a setup based on ...e6 and ...Bd6. While I still believe that setup is excellent, it clearly fits much better with the Queen's Gambit than with the Slav. } 
4. e3 { By far, the most common move. White keeps the c-pawn flexible, allowing both c4 in one move and Nc3 in some moments. } Nc6 { Continuing with our usual development scheme. } 
5. Nbd2 Bg4 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gf8e7,Ge8g8]} { This is our setup. The upside is developing the bishop outside the pawn chain so it will never get locked in. Also, the pin of the f3-knight makes c4 less tempting for White, as then we would have excellent pressure against the d4-pawn.

The big downside of ...Bg4 is that the bishop can easily get harassed by some combination of h3/g4/Nh4. However, from the Slav chapters, we got familiarized with the idea of giving it up for a knight already, so it should make us less nervous here. } 
6. c3 {[%mdl 32768]} { The main move, and I believe what White will play automatically in 90% of the games. } e6 
7. Qb3 Qc8 { Necessary, as there is no other good way to defend the b7-pawn. } 
8. h3 Bh5 { Without the possibility of trading dark-squared bishops with ...Bd6, we don't want to give up our bishop. } 
9. Nh4 { The main and most ambitious move. White intends to win the bishop pair. } Be7 ( { In practical play, it has been more common to enter the Carlsbad structure with } 9...cxd4 { followed by ...Qd7 and ...Bd6, actually even transposing to the Exchange Caro-Kann.

However, whenever possible, I prefer to avoid trading on d4 for practical reasons. It will simply be harder for White to play the middlegame here. } ) 
10. g4 { The point of White's play. But once again, from the Slav, we have gotten used to the idea of giving up our light-squared bishop for a knight in return for provoking some pawn weaknesses in White's camp. } Bg6 
11. Nxg6 hxg6 { A strategically interesting position. White has the bishop pair, and we lack immediate counterplay, but our structure is solid, and we have slightly more central space. Interestingly, both sides have some problems with their king. White doesn’t want to castle short due to h3 and g4, but long castle is hard to achieve due to the c-file pin. Therefore, White's king often stays in the center or even walks slowly via f1 to g2.

For Black, though, things aren't that obvious either. Castling long is rather dangerous as White can open up the c-file quickly, but if we castle kingside too soon, White might push their h- and g-pawns. In general, I believe we should dare to castle short and meet the kingside push by opening up the center. } 
12. Be2 { The best square for the bishop. This is probably the most theoretically critical position in our London repertoire. } cxd4 { I've said numerous times that we don't want to take prematurely on d4, but with White having snatched our light-squared bishop, things are a bit different. The reason we take now is that we want to see how White recaptures in order to react accordingly. } 
13. exd4 { For any London Player, this feels like an automatic recapture, but it's definitely not the only option. } a6 { Preparing ...b5, one of our main strategic ideas. But there is another very important detail here: we keep our queen on c8 for a move longer to prevent White from castling long. }
14. Kf1 {[%cal Gf1g2]} ( { Now, } 14.O-O-O?? { would run into } 14...Nxd4 { winning immediately due to the pin on the c-file. } ) { Another typical move for these positions. The king is relatively safe on g2. } Qd7 { Logical! Now that White can't castle long, we have no use for our queen on c8. } 
15. Kg2 O-O {[%cal Ge7d6,Ge6e5]} { This is what I was talking about earlier. It is a little risky castling into White's advanced pawns, but our counterplay in the center comes quite fast. } 
16. Be3 Bd6 {[%cal Gd7c7]} 
17.-- ( { Taking control over the dark squares. White has the bishop pair, but I rather fancy our counterplay chances. To me, it looks like a rather pleasant position to play. For instance, } 17.Rae1 Rae8 18.Nf3 Qc7 { intending either ...b5 or even ...Ne4 followed by ...f5, in both cases with excellent counterplay. } )
