1. d4 d5 
2. Nf3 Nf6 
3. c3 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { The most serious of White's 3rd move alternatives. Both } 3.e3 { and } ) ( 3.g3 { are objectively more challenging moves, but only because White can still follow up with c4, transposing to other parts of our repertoire. } ) ( 3.c3 { was also recommended by Le Quang Liem in his LTR London repertoire, so we must take it seriously. } ) c6 ( { The most solid move. Objectively, } 3...c5 { might be the strongest move, but then we would be a full tempo down to our repertoire! We play } ) ( 3...c6 { to develop our light-squared bishop, after which the annoying move Qb3 can be safely met by ...Qb6. } ) ( 3...Bf5 4.Qb3 Qc8 { is what I played myself when facing 3.c3 in the last Olympiad. It also makes perfect sense. After } 5.c4 dxc4 6.Qxc4 { , play resembles a bit the 4.Qc2/4.Qb3 Slav, [/course/140404/10] but White has not yet committed to g3 while we have gotten ...Qc8 for free. My conclusion is that it's fully playable for Black, but 3...c6 looks even simpler. } ) 
4. Qc2 ( { A funny-looking move, which 10 years ago I would just have laughed away. Nowadays, however, it has become increasingly difficult to fight for the advantage in the mainlines, so we see more and more creative sideline attempts, also by the world's very best. The idea of } 4.Qc2 { is to make it harder for us to develop our light-squared bishop. } ) Bg4 { Whenever possible, I like to get this bishop out. } 
5. Ne5 { This is the point of White's play. } Bh5 ( { The most normal reply. Strange moves like } 5...Be6 { are possible, but I believe there is nothing wrong with letting White execute their fancy idea. } ) 
6. Qf5 {[%cal Gf5h3]} { This is the only move that puts any sort of pressure on our position! It looks insane, but the queen intends to go to h3, after which our bishop on h5 becomes vulnerable. It has been tried by creative people like Jorden Van Foreest and is the recommendation of Le Quang Liem in his London course. } Bg6 ( { I believe this ties in well with the rest of our repertoire. We are okay with giving up our light-squared bishop for a knight to gain time and fight for the center. } 6...Nbd7 7.Qh3 Qc8! 8.Qh4 Nxe5 9.dxe5 Qg4 { becomes an incredible mess that looks okay for Black, but there is no reason at all to enter such concrete play with long lines. } ) 
7. Qh3 {[%cal Ge5g6]} Bxb1 { Forced, as White was threatening Nxg6. } 
8. Rxb1 e6 { So, we have once again given up the bishop pair. This time, we have a slight lead in development (or will get it soon) and, as usual, an incredibly solid structure. The knight has also gone to e5 a bit too early, making it easier for us to trade it off. } 
9. e3 { The most normal move, catching up in development while not allowing any bishop to get traded. } Nbd7 
10. Nxd7 ( { In general, White prefers to keep the knights on the board, but here it would cost a bit too much time to retreat. } 10.Nf3 Bd6 { intending a quick ...e5 gives us excellent counterplay. } ) Qxd7 
11. Bd3 Bd6 
12. O-O { When first checking this line, I was slightly worried that we might drift into a slightly worse position long-term here. However, we have a surprising resource that promises us excellent counterplay. } h5! {[%cal Gf6g4,Ge8c8][%csl Rh3]} { A very good move! Somehow it turns out that the queen on h3 is seriously misplaced, inviting us to create play against it. Not having castled also means that we can castle long next, and suddenly all White's hopes of a long grind disappear. } 
13. f3 {[%cal Rf6g4]} { Preventing ...Ng4. } O-O-O { We should not think of this as going all in, but rather as starting serious and healthy counterplay. We are unlikely to deliver checkmate, but the pressure created at least forces White to think about their defense. } 
14. b4 Kb8 { Highlighting another important factor of the position. Without knights, it's actually challenging for White to create serious play on the queenside. If White could now place a knight, for instance, on c5, it might get really dangerous, but here we can always meet b5 with ...c5, keeping everything blocked. } 
15. a4 h4 {[%cal Gf6h5,Gf7f5][%csl Rh3]} { The last idea to remember. This is how we want to continue our play. We may intend to push ...g5-g4, but even better is ...Nh5 followed by ...f5, after which the white queen is stuck on the terrible h3-square. }
16.-- ( { Probably White's best bet is to liquidate immediately with } 16.e4 dxe4 17.fxe4 e5! { We can't allow White to play e5. Now the d4-pawn becomes a weakness. } 18.Qxd7 Rxd7 { Intending ...Bc7-...Bb6, with excellent play against the white center. } )
