6. Ne5 ( { The mainline. White obviously intends to capture the c4-pawn, but actually, the more important idea of } 6.Ne5 { is to be able to build a big center with f3 followed by e4. For as long as I have played chess, } ) ( 6.Ne5 { has been considered the most challenging option against the Slav, and I have actually played it myself numerous times with both colors. } ) Nbd7 { Challenging the knight immediately, not giving White the chance to build up in the center with f3 and e4. } ( { It's hard to say whether this is more topical than the big alternative with } 6...e6 { , but I like it a bit more for practical purposes. First of all, the number of forcing lines is slightly lower, but more importantly, the number of possible pawn structures is also considerably lower, meaning that it is much easier to understand what is going on. } ) 
7. Nxc4 Qc7 ( 7...Nb6 { would be the Sokolov System. As long as I have played chess, it has had the reputation of a solid but slightly passive setup for Black, and as far as I am aware, this has not changed much recently either. There is nothing particularly wrong with it, but to my personal taste, it’s a tad too passive. That's why I prefer to both play and recommend the sharper, more double-edged mainlines with } ) ( 7...Qc7 { . } ) 
8. Qd2 {[%cal Gd2f4]} { A funny-looking move with a small trap in mind. } g6! ( { The known antidote. We usually don't fianchetto our dark-squared bishop, but here it works well. } 8...e5?? 9.dxe5 Nxe5 10.Qf4! { is White's point, just winning due to the double attack on e5 and f5. } ) 
9. f3 { This is similar to 8.f3. [/variation/22619752/#/8/w] } e5! 
10. e4 exd4 
11. Ne2 { This has been tried a couple of times by strong players, but to my understanding, it simply doesn't work! } O-O-O! {[%cal Gd7c5][%csl Re1]} ( { This looks like a strong novelty! We sacrifice a piece, but we get a huge attack in return. Just look at the lack of coordination in White's position. } 11...Be6 { is completely fine for Black (but less fun!) and offered as an alternative. [/variation/23178697/#/11/b] } ) 
12. exf5 { Nothing else makes any sense for White. } Nc5 {[%cal Rc5b3,Gd4d3]} { Threatening ...Nb3, but also intending to push the d-pawn. } 
13. Ra3 { The only reasonable move to cover the b3-square. } d3 
14. Nf4 b5! { Important - we have to keep up the pressure. It looks risky to advance the pawns in front of our own king, but the position is a bit too concrete for such considerations. } 
15. axb5 cxb5 
16. Rc3! {[%mdl 32768]} { The only move not to lose immediately. It's clear that this is no longer that theoretically relevant, but I cannot help but show a couple more moves for aesthetical pleasure. } Bh6 { Simply activating our last two pieces. } 
17. b4 { Again, the only move not to be completely lost. Good luck finding that... } Rhe8+ 
18. Kd1 Re2! {[%csl Rd2]} { The reason I wanted to continue the line. A fantastic move that actually traps (!) the White queen. White is not lost, as they can give up their queen for a couple of pieces, but we are definitely in the driver's seat. } 
