5. a4 ( { By far, the mainline. White stops us from playing ...b5, which otherwise would mean we would keep our c4-pawn alive. There are two big downsides of the move } 5.a4 { though. The first is obvious - it gives us an extra tempo so that we are in time for } 5...Bf5 { , both developing our bishop and preventing the e4-push.

The other perhaps slightly less obvious downside is that the b4-square gets weakened. It might not sound like a lot, but it's, in fact, a huge thing. Very often, a bishop on b4 will be able to stay there forever, putting pressure on White's position. Equally important is that whenever Black plays ...a5 later, it becomes very hard for White to open up the queenside later on. This is a huge reason why we can often even castle long in the mainlines. } ) Bf5 { Developing the bishop and preventing e4. Now White again has a big choice, depending on how ambitious and concrete they want to be. } 
6. Ne5 ( { The mainline. White obviously intends to capture the c4-pawn, but actually, the more important idea of } 6.Ne5 { is to be able to build a big center with f3 followed by e4. For as long as I have played chess, } ) ( 6.Ne5 { has been considered the most challenging option against the Slav, and I have actually played it myself numerous times with both colors. } ) Nbd7 { Challenging the knight immediately, not giving White the chance to build up in the center with f3 and e4. } ( { It's hard to say whether this is more topical than the big alternative with } 6...e6 { , but I like it a bit more for practical purposes. First of all, the number of forcing lines is slightly lower, but more importantly, the number of possible pawn structures is also considerably lower, meaning that it is much easier to understand what is going on. } ) 
7. Nxc4 Qc7 ( 7...Nb6 { would be the Sokolov System. As long as I have played chess, it has had the reputation of a solid but slightly passive setup for Black, and as far as I am aware, this has not changed much recently either. There is nothing particularly wrong with it, but to my personal taste, it’s a tad too passive. That's why I prefer to both play and recommend the sharper, more double-edged mainlines with } ) ( 7...Qc7 { . } ) 
8. g3 { The main move. White anticipates our idea and prepares an excellent square for the bishop on f4. The next couple of moves are basically forced. } e5 
9. dxe5 Nxe5 
10. Bf4 Nfd7 
11. a5 { A move that was briefly popular some years ago, that I even used myself twice to win two nice games, but nowadays, I can no longer see the big point. } g5 { Just as in the Morozevich mainline, we use this tactical idea to release the tension in the center. Here it unsurprisingly seems that the developing move 11.Bg2 [/variation/22619769/#/11/w] is way more useful than a4-a5. } 
12. Bxe5 ( { Trying to make concrete use of the pawn on a5. Against both } 12.Nxe5 { and } ) ( 12.Ne3 { we simply have a better version of the mainline. } ) Nxe5 
13. Qd4 {[%mdl 32768]} { This is similar to the mainlines of the Morozevich line, but having a5 instead of Bg2 means we should react differently. } Nxc4! ( { Now much stronger, as White can't get castled as quickly. There is nothing particularly wrong with } 13...f6 { , but trading on c4 is stronger. } 14.Ne3 Be6 { . } ) 
14. Qxh8 ( 14.Qxc4 O-O-O { is great for us - we have the bishop pair for free. } ) Qd8! {[%cal Re1g1,Re1c1]} { This is the key move and one that isn't very easy to spot. With a bishop on g2 and pawn back on a4, White would simply castle, but here the king gets stuck in the center. } 
15. Rd1 ( { The most natural move, but now things quickly go downhill. } 15.Bg2 { is the other option. } 15...Qd2+ 16.Kf1 Qxb2 17.Rd1 Nd2+! { Simply blocking the d-file, enabling us to castle long. } 18.Kg1 O-O-O { We have fantastic compensation for the exchange - just look at the white king! } ) Qxa5 { The point of provoking the rook to d1. } 
16. Bg2 Nxb2 { Everything falls apart for White. } 
17. Rc1 Nc4 
18. O-O Qe5! {[%cal Ga7a5,Ga5a4]} { The last key move. Yes, we have sacrificed an exchange, but with three connected passed pawns on the queenside, the ending is fantastic for us. Keeping the queens on the board would have given White serious counterchances against our king. } 
