6. Ne5 ( { The mainline. White obviously intends to capture the c4-pawn, but actually, the more important idea of } 6.Ne5 { is to be able to build a big center with f3 followed by e4. For as long as I have played chess, } ) ( 6.Ne5 { has been considered the most challenging option against the Slav, and I have actually played it myself numerous times with both colors. } ) Nbd7 { Challenging the knight immediately, not giving White the chance to build up in the center with f3 and e4. } ( { It's hard to say whether this is more topical than the big alternative with } 6...e6 { , but I like it a bit more for practical purposes. First of all, the number of forcing lines is slightly lower, but more importantly, the number of possible pawn structures is also considerably lower, meaning that it is much easier to understand what is going on. } ) 
7. Nxc4 Qc7 ( 7...Nb6 { would be the Sokolov System. As long as I have played chess, it has had the reputation of a solid but slightly passive setup for Black, and as far as I am aware, this has not changed much recently either. There is nothing particularly wrong with it, but to my personal taste, it’s a tad too passive. That's why I prefer to both play and recommend the sharper, more double-edged mainlines with } ) ( 7...Qc7 { . } ) 
8. g3 { The main move. White anticipates our idea and prepares an excellent square for the bishop on f4. The next couple of moves are basically forced. } e5 
9. dxe5 Nxe5 
10. Bf4 Nfd7 
11. Bg2 g5! { An amazing move, invented some 20 years ago by the creative genius Alexander Morozevich. Other moves lead to a pleasant edge for White, but by playing ...g5, we spice things up quite a bit. The idea in itself is simple - the pin along the f4-c7 diagonal is annoying, so we force White to give it up. Now White has three critical options. } ( 11...f6 { has similar ideas but, in my opinion, is a slightly slower move that does not equalize. Nevertheless, check the annotated game Avrukh-Hector. [/variation/22768392/#/11/b] } ) 
12. Ne3 ( { We had already seen all this in Chapter 1,  [/course/140404/1] where I covered White's minor alternatives: the least critical } 12.Nxe5 { that you can check here [/variation/22619769/#/12/w] and the interesting } ) ( 12.Bxe5 { analyzed here. [/variation/22619773/#/12/w] } ) gxf4 
13. Nxf5 { The main move. White goes into a strategically very interesting and double-edged position with opposite-colored bishops and an odd pawn structure for both sides. } O-O-O {[%cal Gd7c5]} { It's pretty clear that short castling will never be an option for Black with such structure, but it's still worth pointing out that castling long sets the tone for the upcoming middlegame.

If we were to speak about pawn structures, it would be tempting to say that White is better due to Black's fragmented kingside. However, things are not that clear - on the queenside, White's pawns are also rather vulnerable and, more importantly, immobile. If we would magically move back White's pawn from a4 to a2, White would be clearly better, if not winning. But as it is, we have excellent squares on b4 and c5 and possibilities to attack the pawns later on.

But the pawn structure will not, at least for the time being, be the most important factor of the position. Instead, that role corresponds to kings' safety, especially if White decides to castle short. While it's true that our king looks safe, we should not take this safety for granted either. Ideas such as b4!? as a sacrifice to open up lines, or even Nb5!? giving up a piece to open the c-file, are very important for us to keep in mind, and they are surprisingly dangerous to deal with. } 
14. Qc2 {[%mdl 32768]} { The overwhelmingly most popular move. White keeps the option of castling both sides. Additionally, by stepping out of the d-file, White might threaten to capture the f4-pawn. } fxg3 { Slightly rare, but interesting. In order to understand why we trade on g3 specifically, we needed to briefly compare it with the alternatives 14...Kb8 [/variation/22619876/#/14/b] and 14...Nc5. [/variation/22619877/#/14/b] } 
15. hxg3 Kb8 { Again, keeping flexible. If White chooses to castle short, we want to push ...h5-...h4. Playing ...h5 before White has castled short is rather pointless, as then White would just castle long instead. Now White needs to decide where to place their king. } 
16. O-O ( { This is rather risky for White.

If } 16.a5 { , it's absolutely necessary to meet it with } 16...a6! { . We never want to allow the pawn to a6, as it would fatally weaken our light squares. But now the inclusion of a5 a6 is in our favour, as the a5-pawn will be an eternal target, while White has not gotten closer to opening up in front of our king. } ) h5! {[%cal Rh8h4]} { Of course! Our attack is very fast. } 
17. Rfc1 {[%cal Gc3b5,Gc3d5][%csl Gf1]} { The main move. White anticipates our idea of ...h4 and an exchange sacrifice on h4 by preparing a square on f1 for their king. Additionally, with a rook on c1, ideas of Nb5 or Nd5 come into the picture. } Nf6! ( { Unfortunately, } 17...h4 { doesn't quite work, but now we can utilize another advantage of our move order - the knight can swing towards the kingside instead of going to c5. } ) 
18. Nb5 Qb6 { There is nothing to be worried about. } 
*

