20. Nbd4 a5! {[%cal Ra4a5,Ye5g6,Yh5h4,Gf8b4]} { We have no direct way to break through, so it's a good moment to stop White's play on the other side. These positions are a bit weird, as, despite the opposite-side castling and the tense play, it's still super hard for either side to break through. Typically, the game’s pace slows down a little bit, and slower maneuvering takes place. One day we want to play ...Ng6 and push ...h4, but it's important not to rush, as we should still be careful about White's counterplay in the center. } 
