What we do next is rather dependent on White. Basically, we are now in a reactive mode, where we wait for White to make a decision - then, we'll try to prove its downside. If White really does nothing at all, then the likes of ...Bb4, ...Nb6, or ...Nf6 are moves to look out for.

Long-term, our main strategic aim is to generate play against the white king, which lacks a solid pawn cover. But it’s important to stress that this does not have to happen fast, as the white king’s problem is an almost eternal factor, which certainly can’t be solved within the next few moves. } 
17. f4 { Romain Edouard tried this move. It's active and pushes our well-placed knight away, but it also creates some holes, while also making it a bit easier for us to know what to do. } Ng4 
18. Ne4 { This is how the engine wants to play it. The knights are beautiful on f5 and e4, but we can just continue with our play without worrying too much. } Bb4 
19. Bf3 { Played by the Croatian GM Davorin Kuljasevic. It's very natural, and I expect quite likely to happen in a practical game. } Ndf6! { It's important to use this knight, as the g4-knight is much more active than the one on d7. } 
20. Nxf6 Nxf6 
21. e4 Nd7! {[%cal Gd7c5][%csl Ra4,Rb2]} { That's how the game continued. This maneuver is important to keep in mind - we are still trying to play against White's king and queenside pawns. } 
22. e5 Nc5 { With excellent counterplay for Black in Kuljasevic-Flumbort, 2017. Due to the vulnerability of the king, White will never be able to attack our kingside pawns. Most probably, a lot of things will get traded along the d-file. } 
