[White "2) The Morozevich Line"]
[Black "Morozevich Line - Alternative 16...Bb4 #3"]
[Date "2023.03.06"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/22619883"]
[ECO "D17"]

1. d4 d5 
2. c4 c6 ( { The Slav! By playing the move ...c6, we support the d5-pawn, but the major difference to } 2...e6 { is that our light-squared bishop is not getting blocked in. Indeed, one of the main advantages of the Slav is that we rarely get bad pieces. Having played the Black side of the Queen's Gambit Declined and the Catalan, I have too many times experienced great suffering due to the c8-bishop never entering the game. That's one of the main reasons I was so happy incorporating the Slav in my Black Repertoire. } ) 
3. Nf3 ( { If White intends to develop both knights on moves 3 and 4, they usually start with } 3.Nf3 { but, from our perspective, it doesn't really matter, as we reply in the same way. } ) Nf6 { The most natural developing move. Now a lot depends on White's next move. If White is in an ambitious mood, they will try to prevent us from developing our light-squared bishop on the next move. If they are more solidly inclined, they allow it, and a slightly slower game emerges. } 
4. Nc3 { Traditionally the main line, and certainly the most natural and logical move. Not only does White develop the knight to the most active square, but in doing so, our most attractive developing move becomes unplayable. } dxc4 { The real Slav! We capture on c4 precisely here, in order to develop our light-squared bishop on the next move without it being hit by Qb3. It does temporarily give up the center, but White will find it surprisingly difficult to get the center rolling in a good way. } ( { In the last couple of years, the move } 4...e6 { , the Semislav, has gotten more popular. One big reason for this is that it can also be used via the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 e6 3.Nf3 d5 4.Nc3 c6 . However, part of the reason I like the Slav so much is precisely that we can play it via 1...d5, thereby avoiding both the Catalan and the Nimzo.

In reality, it feels to me like we have to learn only one opening, instead of three. Stylistically, the Semislav is sharper and more concrete than the real Slav. Normally nothing I mind, but it also means that the amount of existing theory one needs to know as Black is many times bigger than in the real Slav. } ) ( 4...Bf5? { is really what we would like to play, and if given time to play ...e6 as well, all would be good. However, it falls a tempo short. } 5.cxd5! cxd5 6.Qb3 { The point. The idea of Qb3, attacking d5 and b7, is one of the most important themes to be aware of when playing the Slav as Black. Here it more or less just wins on the spot. } 6...b6 7.e4! dxe4 8.Ne5 e6 9.Bb5+ Nbd7 10.Bg5 { White just wins. } ) 
5. a4 ( { By far, the mainline. White stops us from playing ...b5, which otherwise would mean we would keep our c4-pawn alive. There are two big downsides of the move } 5.a4 { though. The first is obvious - it gives us an extra tempo so that we are in time for } 5...Bf5 { , both developing our bishop and preventing the e4-push.

The other perhaps slightly less obvious downside is that the b4-square gets weakened. It might not sound like a lot, but it's, in fact, a huge thing. Very often, a bishop on b4 will be able to stay there forever, putting pressure on White's position. Equally important is that whenever Black plays ...a5 later, it becomes very hard for White to open up the queenside later on. This is a huge reason why we can often even castle long in the mainlines. } ) Bf5 { Developing the bishop and preventing e4. Now White again has a big choice, depending on how ambitious and concrete they want to be. } 
6. Ne5 ( { The mainline. White obviously intends to capture the c4-pawn, but actually, the more important idea of } 6.Ne5 { is to be able to build a big center with f3 followed by e4. For as long as I have played chess, } ) ( 6.Ne5 { has been considered the most challenging option against the Slav, and I have actually played it myself numerous times with both colors. } ) Nbd7 { Challenging the knight immediately, not giving White the chance to build up in the center with f3 and e4. } ( { It's hard to say whether this is more topical than the big alternative with } 6...e6 { , but I like it a bit more for practical purposes. First of all, the number of forcing lines is slightly lower, but more importantly, the number of possible pawn structures is also considerably lower, meaning that it is much easier to understand what is going on. } ) 
7. Nxc4 Qc7 ( 7...Nb6 { would be the Sokolov System. As long as I have played chess, it has had the reputation of a solid but slightly passive setup for Black, and as far as I am aware, this has not changed much recently either. There is nothing particularly wrong with it, but to my personal taste, it’s a tad too passive. That's why I prefer to both play and recommend the sharper, more double-edged mainlines with } ) ( 7...Qc7 { . } ) 
8. g3 { The main move. White anticipates our idea and prepares an excellent square for the bishop on f4. The next couple of moves are basically forced. } e5 
9. dxe5 Nxe5 
10. Bf4 Nfd7 
11. Bg2 g5! { An amazing move, invented some 20 years ago by the creative genius Alexander Morozevich. Other moves lead to a pleasant edge for White, but by playing ...g5, we spice things up quite a bit. The idea in itself is simple - the pin along the f4-c7 diagonal is annoying, so we force White to give it up. Now White has three critical options. } ( 11...f6 { has similar ideas but, in my opinion, is a slightly slower move that does not equalize. Nevertheless, check the annotated game Avrukh-Hector. [/variation/22768392/#/11/b] } ) 
12. Ne3 ( { We had already seen all this in Chapter 1,  [/course/140404/1] where I covered White's minor alternatives: the least critical } 12.Nxe5 { that you can check here [/variation/22619769/#/12/w] and the interesting } ) ( 12.Bxe5 { analyzed here. [/variation/22619773/#/12/w] } ) gxf4 
13. Nxf5 { The main move. White goes into a strategically very interesting and double-edged position with opposite-colored bishops and an odd pawn structure for both sides. } O-O-O {[%cal Gd7c5]} { It's pretty clear that short castling will never be an option for Black with such structure, but it's still worth pointing out that castling long sets the tone for the upcoming middlegame.

If we were to speak about pawn structures, it would be tempting to say that White is better due to Black's fragmented kingside. However, things are not that clear - on the queenside, White's pawns are also rather vulnerable and, more importantly, immobile. If we would magically move back White's pawn from a4 to a2, White would be clearly better, if not winning. But as it is, we have excellent squares on b4 and c5 and possibilities to attack the pawns later on.

But the pawn structure will not, at least for the time being, be the most important factor of the position. Instead, that role corresponds to kings' safety, especially if White decides to castle short. While it's true that our king looks safe, we should not take this safety for granted either. Ideas such as b4!? as a sacrifice to open up lines, or even Nb5!? giving up a piece to open the c-file, are very important for us to keep in mind, and they are surprisingly dangerous to deal with. } 
14. Qc2 { The overwhelmingly most popular move. White keeps the option of castling both sides. Additionally, by stepping out of the d-file, White might threaten to capture the f4-pawn. } fxg3 { Slightly rare, but interesting. In order to understand why we trade on g3 specifically, we needed to briefly compare it with the alternatives 14...Kb8 [/variation/22619876/#/14/b] and 14...Nc5. [/variation/22619877/#/14/b] } 
15. hxg3 Kb8 { Again, keeping flexible. If White chooses to castle short, we want to push ...h5-...h4. Playing ...h5 before White has castled short is rather pointless, as then White would just castle long instead. Now White needs to decide where to place their king. } 
16. O-O-O { The main and most reliable move. White argues that their structure is a bit better and therefore wants a calmer game with castling on the same side. But we should not forget that the pawn is on a4, which could become a serious concern for White later on. Now we have an important choice. } Bb4 ( { This move is completely different in style and philosophy to } 16...a5 { . By playing ...Bb4, we intend swift and concrete play with ...Qa5, ...Nb6, etc., but we lack the stability provided by the nice pawn on a5. With both sides having less stability, the play tends to get more concrete, and this line is no exception. } ) 
17. Kb1 { Again, an almost universally useful move that White would struggle to do without in the long run. } Qa5 {[%cal Gd7b6]} { Continuing with our plan of maximum pressure as soon as possible. } 
18. Rd4 { The best move, and the recommendation by Ivan Cheparinov in his Play 1.d4! book from 2022. } Nb6 { Continuing with our plan. } 
19. Rhh4! {[%mdl 32768]} {[%csl Rb4]} { The best move. White is pinpointing the downside of our strategy - without a pawn on a5, we lack stability for the bishop on b4, and we do not want to be pushed back. } Rxd4 
20. Nxd4 {[%cal Gd4b3]} ( { Threatening to win a piece with Nb3! } 20.Rxd4 Nec4 { is excellent counterplay, as usual. ...Ba3 is an idea. } ) Nbc4 {[%cal Ga5b6]} { Important! We move this knight, as after Nb3 we need to have the b6-square available for our queen. } 
21. Nb3 Qb6 
22. Rd4 { White has played very well over the last five moves and gotten stability on the queenside. Direct attempts to attack no longer work; therefore, we have to accept reality and go for liquidation into a drawish ending. } Rd8! { Starting the trades. From here on out, we play for a draw (which we will rather easily achieve). Sad, yes, I know, but that is how it sometimes goes when we opt for more concrete play that our opponent handles well. } 
23. e3 Na5! 
24.-- ( { Continuing in the same spirit. Trades, trades, trades... } 24.Nxa5 Bxa5 25.Qf5 { The only way to pretend to put some pressure. } 25...Ng6! { As we threaten to pick up a piece on c3 due to the pin, f7 is not hanging yet. } 26.Rxd8+ Qxd8 27.Kc2 Bxc3 28.Kxc3 Qe7 { This position was reached in the correspondence game Bondars-Cerrato, in 2017. One might argue that White has a symbolic edge due to the pawn structure, but it really is very, very little. In general, I would recommend trying to keep the queens on the board and utilizing the queen+knight combo.

A useful idea to keep in mind is ...h5-h4 to liquidate our weakness, making it even more drawish. Another idea is to give up the h-pawn to activate the queen and the knight, not so much to deliver mate, but more realistically to give perpetual check. } )
