10. Nxf5 exf5 {[%cal Rf5e4][%csl Gf5]} { It might look odd to give up the bishop pair and voluntarily accept a doubled pawn, so it's important to understand why we do it. If we think in terms of pawn breaks, we will quickly realize that White is struggling. We control the dark squares on the queenside, making any White pawn push impossible. In the center, pushing d5 would mainly mean giving up further dark squares and giving us an excellent square on d5, so pushing e4 seems to be the only reasonable option. However, apart from being hard to achieve, it also would mean trading off our doubled pawn.

If White simply doesn't want any pawn breaks, it's hard to come up with another plan. Currently, the c1-bishop looks passive, and there is no clear way to maneuver it to a more active position. Meanwhile, we have many easy moves like ...Qe7, ...Rfe8, ...Rad8, etc., all centralizing and improving. } 
11. Qc2 { Developing with tempo, both hitting f5 and eventually preparing e3-e4. } g6 
12. f3 { This really is the way for White to play. As mentioned, if not for the e4-break, the useful moves will simply run out rather soon for White. } Rc8 ( { A useful move, putting the rook on the same file as the opponent’s queen, and more specifically, preparing to push ...c5 next. Another interesting move is } 12...Nb6 { . } ) 
13. Rd1 {[%mdl 32768]} {[%cal Ge3e4][%csl Gd4]} { A logical, albeit slightly slow move. White overprotects d4 in order to play e4. } Nb6 { Forcing the bishop to choose a side. } 
14. Ba2 Qe7 { Stepping out of the way of the White rook. } 
15. e4 { The logical follow-up to White's previous move. } c5! {[%cal Rc5d4,Rf5e4][%csl Rc1]} { Well-timed. Again we are utilizing our c8-rook towards White's queen. To me, it looks like we have excellent counterplay, especially as the bishop is still on c1. }
16.-- ( { The only move not losing any material immediately is } 16.d5 { , but it is a rather sad strategic concession, giving up the dark squares. } 16...fxe4 { The simplest. Just trading off some pieces and taking control over the dark squares in the center. } 17.Nxe4 Nxe4 18.Qxe4 Qxe4 19.fxe4 c4! { is the typical move in such positions. The a2-bishop is now quite bad, and our bishop can become an excellent blockading piece on d6. Also, we should not forget that the a4-pawn is hanging. } )
