The other perhaps slightly less obvious downside is that the b4-square gets weakened. It might not sound like a lot, but it's, in fact, a huge thing. Very often, a bishop on b4 will be able to stay there forever, putting pressure on White's position. Equally important is that whenever Black plays ...a5 later, it becomes very hard for White to open up the queenside later on. This is a huge reason why we can often even castle long in the mainlines. } ) Bf5 { Developing the bishop and preventing e4. Now White again has a big choice, depending on how ambitious and concrete they want to be. } 
6. e3 ( { In my view, the most classical way to play for White. While 6.Ne5 [/variation/22619752/#/6/w] is arguably the most ambitious, } 6.e3 { is a solid way to get an interesting middlegame while at the same time not lacking venom. Historically, what first comes to mind is the World Championship Match in 2005, where this line was debated heavily between Kramnik and Topalov. Lately, it has gone slightly out of fashion but is still a regular choice of classical players such as Sargissian and Korobov. White simply intends to recapture the c4-pawn with the bishop, castle short, and then start preparing e3-e4. } ) e6 
7. Bxc4 Bb4 { This is important. Our idea is probably to push ...e5 in the long run, but here it is much more important to prevent White from playing e4. } 
8. O-O O-O { Now White has to choose between two different ways of fighting for the initiative - either trying to push e3-e4 or going after our bishop pair. } 
9. Qb3 { This used to be a big line but has now fallen completely out of fashion. } c5!? {[%cal Gb8c6,Rc6a5]} { Trying to equalize immediately. } 
10. dxc5 a5 { This is a bit rare. Normally we don't combine ...c5 and ...a5 - it weakens the b5-square. However, here we claim that the queen on b3 is misplaced and will come under attack later on. } 
11. Rd1 {[%mdl 32768]} { The most common move in practical play. } Nbd7 ( { I like this move! It's much rarer than } 11...Qe7 { , but it's a natural idea to try taking back the c5-pawn with the knight. } ) 
12. c6 { Presumably, the reason why people have refrained from 11...Nbd7 previously, but it does seem to work out pretty well for us. } bxc6 {[%cal Ga8b8]} 
13. Ne5 { Again definitely the most tempting move. White wants to trade on d7 in order to push e4 later on. } Nxe5! { This is why I got attracted to @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/1p3ppp/4pn2/p1P2b2/PbB5/1QN1PN2/1P3PPP/R1BR2K1 b - - 1 11@@EndFEN@@ 11...Nbd7 . Sacrificing the queen is always fun; here, it's especially tempting, as the queen on b3 struggles to get back into the game again. } 
14. Rxd8 Rfxd8 {[%cal Ga8b8][%csl Ra1,Rb3,Rc1]} 
15.-- ( { Materially, we have almost enough for the queen, but White struggles to get out with their pieces, whereas all ours are excellently placed. With accurate play, White should probably be okay, but it looks so much more fun to play as Black!

For example, } 15.Be2 { Intending to give back a pawn with e4 next, to free the c1-bishop. } 15...Ne4! { Preventing e4, and playing for domination. We should not worry about trading pieces, as the important thing is that the c1-bishop and the a1-rook never get out. } 16.Nxe4 Bxe4 17.f3 Bd3 { Intending to double on the d-file after the bishop trade.

White still has a long way to go before developing the c1-bishop. With accurate play, they will probably manage to give the queen up for a rook and knight in order to equalize, but even this is not so easy. } )
