6. e3 ( { In my view, the most classical way to play for White. While 6.Ne5 [/variation/22619752/#/6/w] is arguably the most ambitious, } 6.e3 { is a solid way to get an interesting middlegame while at the same time not lacking venom. Historically, what first comes to mind is the World Championship Match in 2005, where this line was debated heavily between Kramnik and Topalov. Lately, it has gone slightly out of fashion but is still a regular choice of classical players such as Sargissian and Korobov. White simply intends to recapture the c4-pawn with the bishop, castle short, and then start preparing e3-e4. } ) e6 
7. Bxc4 Bb4 { This is important. Our idea is probably to push ...e5 in the long run, but here it is much more important to prevent White from playing e4. } 
8. O-O O-O { Now White has to choose between two different ways of fighting for the initiative - either trying to push e3-e4 or going after our bishop pair. } 
9. Qe2 {[%mdl 32768]} { The main move. White intends to push e3-e4. } Nbd7 { This is how Topalov-Kramnik went and was for many years the mainline. However, I believe it is both too theoretical and much tougher to play than our line. } 
10. e4! {[%csl Rf5]} { This is the point. As the f5-bishop is hanging, we are not in time to win the e4-pawn. } *

