In reality, it feels to me like we have to learn only one opening, instead of three. Stylistically, the Semislav is sharper and more concrete than the real Slav. Normally nothing I mind, but it also means that the amount of existing theory one needs to know as Black is many times bigger than in the real Slav. } ) ( 4...Bf5? { is really what we would like to play, and if given time to play ...e6 as well, all would be good. However, it falls a tempo short. } 5.cxd5! cxd5 6.Qb3 { The point. The idea of Qb3, attacking d5 and b7, is one of the most important themes to be aware of when playing the Slav as Black. Here it more or less just wins on the spot. } 6...b6 7.e4! dxe4 8.Ne5 e6 9.Bb5+ Nbd7 10.Bg5 { White just wins. } ) 
5. e4 {[%mdl 32768]} { The Geller Gambit! For those of you who are too young to know about this legendary player, Geller was an incredibly strong player, especially in the 1950-1970s, with a plus score against many of the World Champions. This gambit highlights his style very well, going for the initiative at all costs.

While he won many beautiful attacking games here, Geller's way of playing the gambit hasn't really stood the test of time. However, in the modern era, some new computer-approved ways of playing for White have resulted in the gambit gaining a bit of popularity again. A player that strongly comes to mind is the ever-creative Daniil Dubov. } b5 
6. e5 { Geller's original way of playing, which has proven a bit too straightforward. By placing a pawn on e5, White secures a kingside space advantage for the rest of the game. Still, nowadays, players are quite a bit stronger at defending than Geller's opponents were 50 years ago... } Nd5 
7. a4 { Putting some pressure on our queenside, but we have it all under control. } e6 { It's important not to try to develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain, as it would leave our queenside too vulnerable. One day we will eventually be able to push ..c5, opening up the long diagonal for our bishop. } 
8. Be2 { This is the other way for White to play. While it's objectively stronger than 8.axb5, [/variation/22637572/#/8/w] it's still a rather odd way of playing, as White has a lousy version of these positions. Normally they have their pawn on e4, waiting for an appropriate moment to push either e5 or d5, but with the pawn committed to e5 already, it's much easier for us to know what to do. } a6 { A good move, overprotecting b5 so that we won't have to take on c3. } 
9. axb5 { Natural, in order to get an improved version of Geller's plan. } Bb4! {[%cal Rb4e1][%csl Gd5]} { Very strong. We keep the d5-knight on the board. } 
10. Bd2 Bxc3 
11. bxc3 cxb5 {[%cal Gb8c6,Yb5b4][%csl Gd5]} { Showing the point of why we needed ...a6. Next, we play ...Nc6, after which we have all sorts of counterplay, for example, undermining the d4-pawn by pushing ...b4. } 
