8. axb5 {[%mdl 32768]} { Forcing us to give up our d5-knight, but also straightening out our pawn chain. } Nxc3 
9. bxc3 cxb5 
10. Ng5 { White is playing very aggressively, but there is no positional foundation for such play, which means that it is likely to backfire. } Bb7 
11. Qh5 { Forcing some weaknesses in our position. } g6 
12. Qg4 Be7 
13. Be2 { Geller himself had this position twice, winning and losing one game. However, from an objective point of view, White hasn’t really gotten any real compensation for the pawn. Normally, when White sacrifices a pawn in this way, at least one or two of Black's minor pieces are terrible. Here, however, we don't have any bad pieces, which means we easily fend off the attack. } ( 13.h4 { is rarely something to be worried about here, as we don't mind blocking the kingside. } 13...h5! 14.Qg3 Bd5 { Our king does not need to castle anytime soon or, indeed, probably ever. Instead, continuing to push the queenside pawns will be a simple and effective plan. Our ideas include ...Nc6, ...a5 and ...b4. } ) Bd5! {[%cal Gb8c6,Ga7a5,Gb5b4][%csl Ge6]} { An excellent move that Geller never faced. We overprotect e6, but more importantly, we prepare to develop our knight not to d7 but to the much more active c6-square. After that, we can play in many different ways, for example, starting to push our queenside pawns. White simply lacks the firepower to break through. } 
