10. Ne4 h6 {[%cal Rc1g5]} { This requires some explanation, as in other lines we were happy to let White play Bg5 and trade the dark-squared bishops. So what is the difference? The main goal for White in trading the dark-squared bishops is to access the d6-square for the knight. In the other line, [/variation/22637570/#/10/b] we had our bishop still on c8, but now it's on b7, where it will be hanging after a later Nd6. Therefore, we take the time to stop Bg5 altogether. } ( { That being said, } 10...Be7 { wouldn't be bad either; it's just that } ) ( 10...h6 { is more ambitious. } ) 
11. Bd2 { As White is not getting anywhere on the kingside, they should switch to some queenside action. This prepares b3, to open up a second front. } a5 {[%cal Yb5b4]} { Slightly surprising. The point is that on the kingside, White can't really do anything, so they really need to open up the queenside. By playing ...a5, we are getting ready to block the position after White's most natural follow-up. } 
12. b3 { Most natural. If other moves, we complete our development with ...Nd7, ...Be7, etc. } cxb3 
13. Qxb3 ( 13.axb5?? { Something a bit similar happened in one of Geller's games. } 13...a4 { Suddenly, the b3 and a4-pawns are just marching. Black is completely winning! } ) b4 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gd8c7,Ge8c8]} { Now we see the point of ...a5 - White can't play a5 themselves, so it's all blocked. That means that we can even castle long, should we want to. } 
14. Rac1 Nd7 
15. Rfe1 Qc7!? {[%cal Ge8c8]} ( { Intending long castling next. The play now resembles more of a Semi-Slav than a normal Slav, but we have an excellent version. By the way, simply playing } 15...Be7 { followed by ...O-O is also fine for Black, but a little less interesting. } ) 
