4. Nc3 { Traditionally the main line, and certainly the most natural and logical move. Not only does White develop the knight to the most active square, but in doing so, our most attractive developing move becomes unplayable. } dxc4 { The real Slav! We capture on c4 precisely here, in order to develop our light-squared bishop on the next move without it being hit by Qb3. It does temporarily give up the center, but White will find it surprisingly difficult to get the center rolling in a good way. } ( { In the last couple of years, the move } 4...e6 { , the Semislav, has gotten more popular. One big reason for this is that it can also be used via the move order @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 e6 3.Nf3 d5 4.Nc3 c6 . However, part of the reason I like the Slav so much is precisely that we can play it via 1...d5, thereby avoiding both the Catalan and the Nimzo.

In reality, it feels to me like we have to learn only one opening, instead of three. Stylistically, the Semislav is sharper and more concrete than the real Slav. Normally nothing I mind, but it also means that the amount of existing theory one needs to know as Black is many times bigger than in the real Slav. } ) ( 4...Bf5? { is really what we would like to play, and if given time to play ...e6 as well, all would be good. However, it falls a tempo short. } 5.cxd5! cxd5 6.Qb3 { The point. The idea of Qb3, attacking d5 and b7, is one of the most important themes to be aware of when playing the Slav as Black. Here it more or less just wins on the spot. } 6...b6 7.e4! dxe4 8.Ne5 e6 9.Bb5+ Nbd7 10.Bg5 { White just wins. } ) 
5. g3 e6 ( { This is a rare move, but actually really annoying for us! The reason it's rare is that it gives Black the possibility of transposing either to a Grunfeld (by playing } 5...g6 { ) or to a Semi-Slav (with } ) ( 5...b5 { or } ) ( 5...e6 { , as in the course). } { If you have the Grünfeld on your repertoire, I believe 5...g6 is an excellent solution. But if you don't, the Semi-Slav has to be entered. } ) ( { Starting with } 5...b5 { is also reasonable, but I prefer not to weaken the long diagonal too soon. } ) 
6. Bg2 ( { Or } 6.Ne5 Nbd7 { first. } ) Nbd7 { This is important. We stop Ne5 before playing ...b5. } 
7. O-O {[%mdl 32768]} b5 { Now that Ne5 is stopped, we can play ...b5 without worries. } 
8. Ng5 { A sideline that got a little bit of popularity for a while, but it doesn't seem to scare Black very much. } Qb6 { Necessary to protect both c6 and b5. } 
9. e4 h6 
10. Nxe6 { Another crazy idea of the ever-creative Daniil Dubov. White is willing to give up a full piece to open up in front of our king. It shouldn't work, but it looks scary, and we need to know how to handle it. } fxe6 
11. e5 Nd5 
12. Qg4 { This is White's point - we lack a convenient way of defending f7. } Kf7 { Ugly, but there are no better options. } 
13. Be4 ( { Scary-looking, but it does stop a later Ne4. } 13.a4 { Dubov's move, but it's a bit too much. } 13...b4 14.Ne2 Be7 { and, objectively, Black was winning in Dubov-Ter Sahakyan, 2015. If need be, we can even add a further defender with ...Nf8. } ) Nb8 {[%cal Gc8e6,Yb8a6,Gf7e7,Ge7d7,Gd7c7]} { Looks insane, but we are preparing to run our king away to relative safety on the queenside. Therefore, the e6-pawn needs more defending, and the d7-square needs clearance. The knight could join the game later on via a6-b4. } 
