5. g3 e6 ( { This is a rare move, but actually really annoying for us! The reason it's rare is that it gives Black the possibility of transposing either to a Grunfeld (by playing } 5...g6 { ) or to a Semi-Slav (with } ) ( 5...b5 { or } ) ( 5...e6 { , as in the course). } { If you have the Grünfeld on your repertoire, I believe 5...g6 is an excellent solution. But if you don't, the Semi-Slav has to be entered. } ) ( { Starting with } 5...b5 { is also reasonable, but I prefer not to weaken the long diagonal too soon. } ) 
6. Bg2 ( { Or } 6.Ne5 Nbd7 { first. } ) Nbd7 { This is important. We stop Ne5 before playing ...b5. } 
7. O-O b5 { Now that Ne5 is stopped, we can play ...b5 without worries. } 
8. e4 { The only real way to fight for the initiative. } b4 
9. e5 ( { A relatively rare move, played recently by Ding Liren. It is an attempt to avoid the sharpest complications and just get a sound middlegame. } 9.Na4 { is possible, but here the knight is slightly offside, as we can keep control over the c5-square. } 9...Be7 { We should not be too greedy and take e4, as it would open up the long diagonal too soon. Instead, just finish development with ...O-O and ...Ba6, with a healthy position. } ) { The most normal and most critical move. } Nd5 
10. Ne4 { So we forced White's knight to e4 with tempo, but the problem for White is that it is the wrong knight! The f3-knight is in the way, as White would like to bring their queen over to h5 or g4. Therefore, White will find it hard to create serious threats here. } Be7 
11. Bg5 { A logical move, but as we have seen before, allowing a knight to d6 is certainly not the end of the world for us. } O-O 
12. Bxe7 Qxe7 {[%cal Ga7a5,Yc4c3,Gc8a6]} { This looks fine for us. As soon as the knight leaves e4, we are ready to push ...c3, keeping our c-pawn alive. } 
13. Re1 {[%cal Gf3d2,Gd2c4,Gc4d6]} { Sipke Ernst's recommendation in his 'Seriously Shock the Semi-Slav'. The idea is to reroute the f3-knight via d2 to c4-d6. } a5 { In my view, the most logical and ambitious move! The bishop will find itself much safer on a6 with the pawn already on a5. } ( 13...c3 { is usually the more solid reply. We intend to give back the c-pawn in order to free ourselves and equalize the game. } 14.bxc3 bxc3 15.Qc1 { White has other moves as well, but none that really alters the character of the position. } 15...Bb7 16.Nxc3 Nxc3 17.Qxc3 c5 { White is optically a touch more active, but without weaknesses it should basically just be equal. } ) 
14. Nfd2 {[%mdl 32768]} { This would be the most straightforward continuation, but here our counterplay comes fast. } c3 
15. bxc3 bxc3 
16. Nc4 Ba6 
17. Ncd6 { The knights look very annoying, but in fact, they don't really attack anything. Another point that is important to mention is that our pawn is still on c6, so White has no way to open the center. } f6! {[%cal Rf6e5][%csl Re5,Rd4]} { The key idea for generating counterplay here. It's important not to let White pick up the c3-pawn in peace. Here, we get serious counterplay in the center in the meantime. } 
