9. e5 ( { A relatively rare move, played recently by Ding Liren. It is an attempt to avoid the sharpest complications and just get a sound middlegame. } 9.Na4 { is possible, but here the knight is slightly offside, as we can keep control over the c5-square. } 9...Be7 { We should not be too greedy and take e4, as it would open up the long diagonal too soon. Instead, just finish development with ...O-O and ...Ba6, with a healthy position. } ) { The most normal and most critical move. } Nd5 
10. Ne4 { So we forced White's knight to e4 with tempo, but the problem for White is that it is the wrong knight! The f3-knight is in the way, as White would like to bring their queen over to h5 or g4. Therefore, White will find it hard to create serious threats here. } Be7 
11. Qc2 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { This has been the most common move so far, although the entire 8...b4 line has very few games. } 11.Re1 { was employed in another recent correspondence game; we can play in the same manner } 11...a5 12.Bg5 O-O 13.Bxe7 Qxe7 14.Nfd2 c3! { Again, this idea, similarly to our main line. } 15.bxc3 bxc3 16.Nb1 Qb4! { gave Black a decent position in Davidov-Kotzev, 2022. ...Ba6 is an important idea, and we are ready to push ...c5 soon and equalize. } ) a5 { Played in the correspondence game Talpak-Sampieri from 2018. As usual, it's a good idea to secure a safe spot for our bishop on a6. We will not be in time to save the c4-pawn, but while White wins it back, we complete development and push ...c5. } 
12. Nfd2 c3 { The game continued like this. Sacrificing with ...c3 is often a good idea, as we get access to the b4-square and force the trade of White's stronger knight. } 
