[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Classical Slav"]
[White "6) The Slow Slav"]
[Black "Slow Slav - 5.Bd3 #1"]
[Date "2023.03.06"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/22637655"]
[ECO "D12"]

1. d4 d5 
2. c4 c6 ( { The Slav! By playing the move ...c6, we support the d5-pawn, but the major difference to } 2...e6 { is that our light-squared bishop is not getting blocked in. Indeed, one of the main advantages of the Slav is that we rarely get bad pieces. Having played the Black side of the Queen's Gambit Declined and the Catalan, I have too many times experienced great suffering due to the c8-bishop never entering the game. That's one of the main reasons I was so happy incorporating the Slav in my Black Repertoire. } ) 
3. Nf3 ( { If White intends to develop both knights on moves 3 and 4, they usually start with } 3.Nf3 { but, from our perspective, it doesn't really matter, as we reply in the same way. } ) Nf6 { The most natural developing move. Now a lot depends on White's next move. If White is in an ambitious mood, they will try to prevent us from developing our light-squared bishop on the next move. If they are more solidly inclined, they allow it, and a slightly slower game emerges. } 
4. e3 {[%mdl 32768]} { The so-called Slow Slav. A seemingly modest move, but I would argue it's even the single most critical line against the Slav on higher levels nowadays.

The reason is, as so often in modern chess, that the somewhat less forcing nature of the position makes it harder for Black players to 'kill' the game by making it too forcing. This does not bother us, however, as we are more than happy to get an interesting fight with lots of play for both sides! } Bf5 {[%cal Ge7e6][%csl Yf5]} { As a rule of thumb, when we can, we should always develop our bishop outside the pawn chain. When doing so, we must always be careful about our weakened queenside. Especially the move Qb3 should be kept in mind, as the b7-pawn lacks support. Here, due to White's somewhat slow move 4.e3, this is not really an issue. }
5. Bd3 ( { At this point, } 5.Qb3 { is not dangerous at all. We can go } 5...Qc7 { as, due to White having played e3 already, we never have to worry about Bf4. Now } 6.cxd5 cxd5 { would transpose here. [/variation/22637662/#/6/b] } ) { Another innocent-looking move. Compared to 5.Nc3 e6 6.Nh4, [/variation/22637665/#/6/w] it is not theoretically challenging, but a decent practical choice where White's play is often rather straightforward. Luckily, chess is a complicated enough game that the most simplistic ways are rarely the best! } Bxd3 { In some sense, the light-squared bishop is Black's 'bad' one, but more important is the fact that White has a space advantage; therefore, trades are, in principle, beneficial for us as Black. } 
6. Qxd3 e6 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8]} { Natural development. } 
7. O-O Be7 { If White plays an early Nc3, it's usually an interesting option to go ...Bb4 instead, but as White delayed it here, we don't have this possibility.

It might look more active to place the bishop on d6, but we need to understand what White wants. Their main plan is to push e4, opening up for the c1-bishop and gaining more space. When that happens, we want the d-file open to put pressure on the d4-pawn. Additionally, White might be hoping for some play against our king later on, and for that, the bishop is more useful on e7, preventing, for instance, Ng5. } 
8. Nbd2 { This usually leads to the same thing, as after e4, we take anyway. } O-O 
9. Rd1 ( { Overprotecting d4 to play e4 next. } 9.e4 dxe4 10.Nxe4 c5 { transposes here. [/variation/22637656/#/10/b] } ) Nbd7 ( { The simplest. There are more fancy ways to play against White's slightly strange-looking setup; for instance, } 9...a5!? 10.e4 a4!? { but I see no need to make it more complicated than it is. } ) 
10. e4 dxe4 
11. Nxe4 c5 { Transposing to this line. [/variation/22637658/#/11/b] } 
