6. Nh4 ( { Now something like } 6.Be2 { is too slow! } 6...h6 { Saving our f5-bishop. These positions are really comfortable for Black, as White lacks a clear plan, whereas we will complete our development with ...Nbd7, ...Bd6, and ...O-O. Our bishop will retreat to h7 if needed. } ) { Basically the only challenging move. } Be4 ( { Upping the stakes a bit. In order to win our bishop, White now has to play f3. That could be a useful extra tempo for pushing in the center, but it is also a weakness that makes it a whole lot less tempting to castle kingside. In short, the game simply gets a bit more double-edged.

Historically, } 6...Bg6 { has been the most common move. There is no doubt that it's solid, but even less doubt that it's also solid for White! Usually, a long game emerges where White is a tiny bit better with the bishop pair. I never liked openings in which we are only trying to equalize, and therefore the } ) ( 6...Bg6 { line never really interested me a whole lot from Black's point of view. } ) 
