11. Bc1 { The critical move, trying to remove our disturbing bishop. } Bc4 
12. Bxc4 bxc4 {[%cal Gg7g5]} { Now we threaten to trap the knight on h4, so White has to lose additional time. } 
13. g3 c5 { Striking against the center. } 
14. Qa4+ Nbd7 
15. Qxc4 { White won a pawn, but our counterplay is very strong. This is largely due to the fact that the h4-knight is so much out of play. } cxd4 
16. Qxd4 ( 16.exd4 { is also possible but gives us nice positional compensation. } 16...Be7 { We intend ...O-O, ...Rc8, and then probably ...Nb6-...Nd5. The d5-square, the weak d4-pawn, and the stupid h4-knight are all factors that provide us with decent compensation. } ) Bc5 {[%csl Rd4]} { Developing with tempo. } 
17. Qc4 Rc8 { Threatening some discovered attack. } 
18. Qe2 Ne5 {[%cal Ge8g8,Ge5d3,Gd8d3]} { Black got very nice play for the pawn in So-Shirov, 2022. The extra pawn is not felt at all, all our pieces are great, and White's coordination looks rather bad. } 
