1. d4 d5 
2. c4 c6 ( { The Slav! By playing the move ...c6, we support the d5-pawn, but the major difference to } 2...e6 { is that our light-squared bishop is not getting blocked in. Indeed, one of the main advantages of the Slav is that we rarely get bad pieces. Having played the Black side of the Queen's Gambit Declined and the Catalan, I have too many times experienced great suffering due to the c8-bishop never entering the game. That's one of the main reasons I was so happy incorporating the Slav in my Black Repertoire. } ) 
3. e3 {[%mdl 32768]} { Sometimes White tries this move order in order to reach the Meran, but generally transpose with 4.Nc3 on the next move. } Nf6 
4. Bd3 ( { The only independent option, as } 4.Nc3 Bf5 { transposes to this line. [/variation/22637939/#/4/b] } ) e5! { This is the problem for White and the reason why this line is very rarely tried nowadays. } 
5. Nc3 ( { Now the game transposes to some kind of weird reversed French. } 5.dxe5 dxc4! { is our point: } 6.Bxc4 Qxd1+ 7.Kxd1 Ng4 { Winning back the e5-pawn, after which we are just better. } ) Bb4 ( 5...e4 { is more ambitious and also perfectly playable, but I chose this simpler move for simplicity's sake. } ) 
6. cxd5 { Played in Maly-Giri, 2020. White avoids the IQP, but this looks way too soft to pose any sort of problem. } Qxd5 
7. dxe5 Qxe5 ( 7...Ne4!? { is another interesting option. } ) 
8. Bd2 O-O {[%cal Gb8d7,Gf8d8]} { We have no problems at all. Next up, we can develop our queenside and put a rook on the d-file. } 
