1. d4 d5 
2. c4 c6 ( { The Slav! By playing the move ...c6, we support the d5-pawn, but the major difference to } 2...e6 { is that our light-squared bishop is not getting blocked in. Indeed, one of the main advantages of the Slav is that we rarely get bad pieces. Having played the Black side of the Queen's Gambit Declined and the Catalan, I have too many times experienced great suffering due to the c8-bishop never entering the game. That's one of the main reasons I was so happy incorporating the Slav in my Black Repertoire. } ) 
3. Nc3 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf6 
4. e3 { Once upon a time, this was considered almost by force to lead to the Meran variation of the Semi-Slav. While the Meran is an incredibly interesting opening for both sides, it's outside the scope of our repertoire. Luckily, some 10-15 years ago, another line appeared which enabled Black to avoid the Meran. } Bf5! { The exclam is, of course, not for the objective merits of the move but rather an indication of how happy we should be that the move exists. As we play 4...Bf5 [/variation/22637655/#/4/b] also against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@ 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.e3 , it is also very convenient to do it here. For a long time, though, it was believed to be bad. Since a new way of playing became popular, the verdict has gone back and forth a bit, but I think by now, we can safely say that this line is very healthy for Black, and White is struggling to put any pressure. } 
5. f3 { Seeing that the mainline seems to be working out well for Black, White has recently switched to more creative (or desperate) ways of putting pressure. This move has been a favorite of the young Iranian Maghsoodloo to score some good wins. White intends to push the g- and h-pawns. } h5 {[%cal Rg2g4]} { The solid way - we simply stop g4. The pawn on h5 is in itself a small weakening, but on the other hand, the pawn on f3 is greatly in the way for White as well. The game now tends to be rather calm. } ( 5...e6 6.g4 Bg6 7.h4 h6 { is a super sharp option. It's complicated and, for sure, interesting without being bad, but it's also the sort of line where you need to remember a lot of things for something you are very unlikely to face in a practical game. } ) 
6. Qb3 { Possible, and similar to the immediate 5.Qb3. [/variation/22637942/#/5/w] } Qb6 ( { Necessary here. } 6...Qc7 { is not possible, as the d5-pawn is simply hanging. } ) 
7. cxd5 Qxb3! { Generally speaking, we always want to settle with an isolated doubled b-pawn when given a chance. } 
8. axb3 cxd5! ( { Important! As we don't have any play on the a-file, giving up the center with } 8...Nxd5 9.e4 { does not give us enough counterplay. On the other hand, taking immediately with the pawn on d5 is less of a problem now, as White won't get the b5-square forever. } ) 
9. Nb5 { The critical attempt. Given one more move, we would play ... Nc6 and be ready to meet Nb5 with ...Kd7 again. } Kd7 
10. Rxa7 { Picking up a pawn. } Rxa7 
11. Nxa7 e6 { Due to our lead in development and the fact that White's extra pawn is an isolated doubled one, we are not worried at all. } 
12. Bd2 Nc6 
13. Nxc6 ( 13.Nb5 Bc2 { picks up the b3-pawn immediately. } ) bxc6 {[%cal Gf8d6,Gh8b8][%csl Rb3]} { We have plenty of easy moves. Most likely, White will have to give back one of the b-pawns to equalize the game. } 
