[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Classical Slav"]
[White "7) The Meran Attempt"]
[Black "Meran Attempt - 8.Qb3 with 10.dxe5 #5"]
[Date "2023.03.06"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/22637950"]
[ECO "D10"]

1. d4 d5 
2. c4 c6 ( { The Slav! By playing the move ...c6, we support the d5-pawn, but the major difference to } 2...e6 { is that our light-squared bishop is not getting blocked in. Indeed, one of the main advantages of the Slav is that we rarely get bad pieces. Having played the Black side of the Queen's Gambit Declined and the Catalan, I have too many times experienced great suffering due to the c8-bishop never entering the game. That's one of the main reasons I was so happy incorporating the Slav in my Black Repertoire. } ) 
3. Nc3 Nf6 
4. e3 { Once upon a time, this was considered almost by force to lead to the Meran variation of the Semi-Slav. While the Meran is an incredibly interesting opening for both sides, it's outside the scope of our repertoire. Luckily, some 10-15 years ago, another line appeared which enabled Black to avoid the Meran. } Bf5! { The exclam is, of course, not for the objective merits of the move but rather an indication of how happy we should be that the move exists. As we play 4...Bf5 [/variation/22637655/#/4/b] also against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp2pppp/2p5/3p4/2PP4/8/PP2PPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 3@@EndFEN@@ 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.e3 , it is also very convenient to do it here. For a long time, though, it was believed to be bad. Since a new way of playing became popular, the verdict has gone back and forth a bit, but I think by now, we can safely say that this line is very healthy for Black, and White is struggling to put any pressure. } 
5. cxd5 cxd5 
6. Qb3 {[%csl Rd5,Rb7]} { This is the reason why the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pppp/2p2n2/3p4/2PP4/2N1P3/PP3PPP/R1BQKBNR b KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4...Bf5 move order was for a long time considered dubious. There seems to be no good way of defending both d5 and b7. } Nc6 { Indeed, there is no good way of defending the pawn, but we can sacrifice it! White will have to waste a lot of time with their queen, and in the meantime, we get counterplay in the center. } 
7. Qxb7 { Without this, White's play doesn't make any sense at all. } Bd7 { A sad necessity, but there is no other good way of defending c6. } 
8. Qb3 {[%cal Gb3d1]} { The overwhelmingly most common move. The queen goes back to safety on d1. } Rb8 
9. Qd1 e5 {[%cal Gf8d6,Ge8g8,Yb8b6,Yb6g6,Yg6h6][%csl Gb8,Rb2]} { This is our idea. Normally, we are not allowed to break this quickly in the center in the Slav. It might be a good moment to talk a little bit about what we actually have for our sacrificed pawn.

First of all, we have a slight lead in development. Secondly, our rook on b8 makes it a bit hard for White to develop their queenside. Thirdly, we have many easy moves, like ...Bd6, ...O-O, and so on, eventually creating kingside threats. Another useful idea to keep in mind is to swing the rook over via b6 to g6 or h6 later on.

But I think it's also important to note that White's extra pawn is not so valuable or relevant. The queenside majority is very, very far off from being a factor, and it is simply unlikely ever to happen. } 
10. dxe5 { The main move in practice. White does not want to give us the chance of ...e4. } Nxe5 
11. Be2 { The mainline, and Shankland's recommendation in his 1.d4 repertoire here on Chessable. } ( { White would be ill-advised to keep grabbing pawns as after } 11.Nxd5 Nxd5 12.Qxd5 Bb4+ 13.Bd2 Bxd2+ 14.Qxd2 Qf6 { they will be severely behind in development and struggling to get their pieces out. Tactics already work in Black's favor as } 15.Be2 { can be met with } 15...Rxb2! { as } 16.Qxb2?? Nd3+ { picks up the queen next. As we will see in a subsequent trainable [/variation/24343732/#/14/w], even grabbing the pawn somewhat later is not great, while grabbing it here is just a worse version of the same ideas for White. Black has more than enough compensation. } ) Bd6 
12. Nf3 Nxf3+! { Very important! When I talked earlier about this line changing verdict a couple of times, this is one of the changes I talked about. Before Black understood the importance of this move order, it was thought that White had nice pressure, but by preventing Nd4, we make it very hard for White to do anything at all. } 
13. Bxf3 Qc7 {[%csl Rh2]} { Forcing White to create a weakness before castling. } 
14. h3 O-O 
15. O-O Rfd8 { Activating our last piece. We use this rook as the other one is active along the b-file and potentially able to switch over to the kingside via b6. The arising position is a little bit of a strange one. We are a pawn down and can't get it back anytime soon, but we are also not giving mate. Again, the point is more that it's tough for White to get out without giving the pawn back. It looks very easy for us to play, but the only downside is that if White plays cynically and gives back the pawn at a good moment, the position tends to become quite drawish quickly. } 
16. a4 {[%mdl 32768]} { Another common move. White intends to stabilize a future knight on b5 but is also stopping our ...Bb5 later on. } Bh2+ { Of course, we give this useful check also here. } 
17. Kh1 Be5 
18. Nxd5 { This has been tried a couple of times, for instance, by the French super-GM Bacrot. It's useful to know how to react. } Nxd5 
19. Bxd5 Bxh3 { The most straightforward response. We regain the piece immediately. } 
20. gxh3 Qd7 
21. Kg2 { Else, it's simply mate. } Qxd5+ 
22. Qxd5 Rxd5 { We are still a pawn down, but, as usual, the b2-pawn can be taken whenever we feel like it. This was eventually drawn in Al-Sayed - Matlakov, 2015. } 
