[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Classical Slav"]
[White "8) The Fianchetto Variation"]
[Black "Fianchetto - 5.Bg2 #1"]
[Date "2023.03.06"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/22638412"]
[ECO "D11"]

1. d4 d5 
2. c4 c6 ( { The Slav! By playing the move ...c6, we support the d5-pawn, but the major difference to } 2...e6 { is that our light-squared bishop is not getting blocked in. Indeed, one of the main advantages of the Slav is that we rarely get bad pieces. Having played the Black side of the Queen's Gambit Declined and the Catalan, I have too many times experienced great suffering due to the c8-bishop never entering the game. That's one of the main reasons I was so happy incorporating the Slav in my Black Repertoire. } ) 
3. Nf3 ( { If White intends to develop both knights on moves 3 and 4, they usually start with } 3.Nf3 { but, from our perspective, it doesn't really matter, as we reply in the same way. } ) Nf6 { The most natural developing move. Now a lot depends on White's next move. If White is in an ambitious mood, they will try to prevent us from developing our light-squared bishop on the next move. If they are more solidly inclined, they allow it, and a slightly slower game emerges. } 
4. g3 {[%mdl 32768]} Bf5 ( { The Fianchetto Variation is a popular try for White, mainly because of its simplicity - it can be played against the King's Indian and Grünfeld as well as being combined with the Catalan. For instance, Srinath Narayanan does precisely that in his Catalan LTR on Chessable. Indeed, should you have the Grünfeld on your repertoire, then } 4...g6 { is an excellent move that I have played many times myself. However, sticking to the pure Slav is also perfectly possible, even in various ways. } ) ( 4...dxc4 { is the most ambitious move, trying to hold onto the pawn, but it's not quite the same without White having committed their knight to c3. Putting the bishop on g4 instead of f5 is also perfectly playable, but in the end, I decided that } ) ( 4...Bf5 { is the move that goes best together with the rest of our repertoire. } ) 
5. Bg2 ( { This is natural but slightly inaccurate or at the least less ambitious than starting with } 5.Nc3 { . } ) h6 { This is the problem for White. Normally, their main idea is to play Nh4 at an appropriate moment, but starting with Bg2 gives us time to save the bishop. } 
6. O-O e6 { White usually plays Nc3 here anyway, transposing to our next line. [/variation/22638413/#/7/w] } 
7. b3 { White often goes for the double fianchetto in the Catalan. However, it works less well against the Slav. The reason is that our light-squared bishop is outside the pawn chain, so we never run the risk of ending up with a bad bishop. } Be7 
8. Bb2 O-O {[%cal Gb8d7,Ga7a5,Gf6e4]} { This is just comfortable for us. We easily complete our development, and then White will lack a real plan, as the e4-break is not easily achievable. } 
*

