13. Be2 { The most common move and a good demonstration of why White rarely plays Bg2 in the beginning. } Rfe8 {[%cal Ge7f8,Ge6e5]} { Preparing to push ...e5 one day, but also giving the bishop a useful square on f8. } 
14. Ne5 { This was played in a correspondence game. It makes sense to physically block ...e5. } Nxe5 ( { The most direct way, though calmer moves like } 14...Bh7 { or } ) ( 14...Bf8 { also make sense. } ) 
15. Bxe5 Nd7 { Immediately hitting the e5-bishop. } 
16. g4 ( { Necessary! } 16.Bc7 Rac8 17.Ba5 e5! { is a much worse version for White - after g4, we can now retreat to e6 with the bishop instead. } ) Bh7 
17. Bc7 {[%mdl 32768]} { Another good move for White. I don't expect too many people to play like this in a game, but it was tried in some correspondence games and looks like good chess, so it is useful to at least be aware of it. } Bf8 { In the correspondence game, the bishop went to f6 instead, but I like to keep that square for the knight instead. } 
18. f4 {[%cal Re6e5]} { White really needs to stop us from pushing ...e5 } Rac8 
19. Ba5 { This is another strange kind of position that happens rather often in this line. It is almost completely blocked, but there is still some action on the kingside. White has some extra space, but we have the easier pawn breaks available. } g5 {[%cal Gf8g7,Gd7f6,Gf6e4]} 
20.-- ( { A typical thrust. We don't want to get too passive, and this gives us the necessary counterplay. } 20.hxg5 hxg5 21.O-O-O Bg7 { is a natural continuation. Next up, we are ready for ...Nf6 and, at the right moment, jump into e4. The slower idea of ...Kf8-e7 followed by contesting the h-file could also make sense. } )
*

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Classical Slav"]
[White "8) The Fianchetto Variation"]
[Black "Fianchetto - 5.Nc3 e6 6.Nh4 with 10.O-O"]
[Date "2023.03.06"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/22638422"]
[ECO "D11"]

1. d4 d5 
2. c4 c6 ( { The Slav! By playing the move ...c6, we support the d5-pawn, but the major difference to } 2...e6 { is that our light-squared bishop is not getting blocked in. Indeed, one of the main advantages of the Slav is that we rarely get bad pieces. Having played the Black side of the Queen's Gambit Declined and the Catalan, I have too many times experienced great suffering due to the c8-bishop never entering the game. That's one of the main reasons I was so happy incorporating the Slav in my Black Repertoire. } ) 
3. Nf3 ( { If White intends to develop both knights on moves 3 and 4, they usually start with } 3.Nf3 { but, from our perspective, it doesn't really matter, as we reply in the same way. } ) Nf6 { The most natural developing move. Now a lot depends on White's next move. If White is in an ambitious mood, they will try to prevent us from developing our light-squared bishop on the next move. If they are more solidly inclined, they allow it, and a slightly slower game emerges. } 
4. g3 Bf5 ( { The Fianchetto Variation is a popular try for White, mainly because of its simplicity - it can be played against the King's Indian and Grünfeld as well as being combined with the Catalan. For instance, Srinath Narayanan does precisely that in his Catalan LTR on Chessable. Indeed, should you have the Grünfeld on your repertoire, then } 4...g6 { is an excellent move that I have played many times myself. However, sticking to the pure Slav is also perfectly possible, even in various ways. } ) ( 4...dxc4 { is the most ambitious move, trying to hold onto the pawn, but it's not quite the same without White having committed their knight to c3. Putting the bishop on g4 instead of f5 is also perfectly playable, but in the end, I decided that } ) ( 4...Bf5 { is the move that goes best together with the rest of our repertoire. } ) 
5. Nc3 e6 ( 5...h6 { is a bit too slow due to } 6.cxd5 cxd5 7.Qb3 { when both d5 and b7 are weak. } ) 
6. Nh4 {[%mdl 32768]} { Traditionally the mainline. Just like in the Slow Slav, [/variation/22637665/#/6/w] White traps our bishop. } dxc4 ( { The mainline. } 6...Be4 { is possible here as well, but it seems to me that g3 is a better setup than e3, as with the bishop on g2 the pawn break with e4 is more easily achievable. Additionally, in the Slow Slav, we often got counterplay (and tricks! [/variation/22637680/#/14/b]) along the h-file and towards the h2-pawn, but here the pawn on g3 prevents that. } ) 
7. Nxf5 exf5 { Now the pawn structure resembles the 6.e3 line. [/variation/22637549/#/10/b] The only difference is the move g3 instead of a4. Therefore, many plans are the same, but there are also some differences. One is that with the pawn still on a2, we don't have the same control over the b4-square, but castling long is a more reasonable approach for White. On the other hand, the move g3 does not always fit in too well with the idea of pushing f3 and e4. } 
8. e3 Bd6!? { This is a bit controversial. For ages, Black automatically played ...Nbd7-...Nb6 to gain control over the d5-square. I believe we could gain from some flexibility, though. The knight could go via d7 to b6 still, but it could also sometimes go a6. Or even immediately to c6, in case we push ...c5. } ( { Another, and perhaps bigger, reason to play } 8...Bd6 { is that it is so rare, meaning our opponents will most probably be less familiar with it! } ) 
9. Bxc4 O-O { Historically speaking, it was believed to be very risky for Black to castle short too early here, as White could try to create threats connected to the g4-push. With the pawn already on a4 (in the 6.e3 Slav [/course/140404/3]), this did not work out well at all for White, but with the pawn back on a2, it becomes much safer for White to castle long later. } 
10. O-O { Played recently by the solid and well-prepared Turkish GM Mustafa Yilmaz, but it's not enough to create any real pressure. } Nbd7 { Now that White committed their king to the kingside, we can safely develop most naturally. } 
11. Re1 Nb6 
12. Bf1 { Solid and natural play, but it allows us to play all the moves we want. } Re8 
13. Bg2 h5!? {[%cal Gd8d7,Ga8d8]} { A nice idea seen in Yilmaz-Durarbayli, 2022. We might intend to push ...h4, but there is also no need to do it anytime soon. It's just very annoying for White to keep it in mind at all times. Next up, we could also just centralize our pieces with ...Qd7, ...Rad8, and so on.

As usual in these positions, the main problem for White is that they lack a good plan. We have no weaknesses they can attack, and there are no tempting pawn breaks. This might be a bit biased, but in practical play, I think Black's position is slightly easier to play. } 
*

