1. d4 d5 
2. c4 c6 ( { The Slav! By playing the move ...c6, we support the d5-pawn, but the major difference to } 2...e6 { is that our light-squared bishop is not getting blocked in. Indeed, one of the main advantages of the Slav is that we rarely get bad pieces. Having played the Black side of the Queen's Gambit Declined and the Catalan, I have too many times experienced great suffering due to the c8-bishop never entering the game. That's one of the main reasons I was so happy incorporating the Slav in my Black Repertoire. } ) 
3. Nc3 Nf6 
4. Bg5 {[%mdl 32768]} { From time to time, this move is played. It feels to me that White is not paying enough attention and thinks it's a normal Queen's Gambit Declined, but it most certainly isn't! } dxc4! { This works very well here. The bishop is simply not very well placed on g5. } 
5. e4 { Some sort of Geller Gambit [/course/140404/4] attempt, but again, the bishop is simply bad on g5. } b5 { Keeping the pawn. } 
6. Nf3 { Now there are many good options } b4 { Very straightforward. } 
7. Na4 Nxe4 {[%cal Re4g5]} { The bishop is exposed on g5. } 
