5. Nh4 { Just as in the Slow Slav, trying to win the bishop is the only attempt [/variation/22637665/#/6/w] to show any ambition at all. } Be4 ( 5...Bg6 { This is not that relevant to us, as we anyway always prefer to flick in ...Be4 to provoke f3, but I still can't resist showing this gorgeous trap that I think is one of the main reasons 4.Nbd2 is so popular for White at club levels. } 6.Qb3 Qb6?! 7.Qh3 { Suddenly, the mating threat will force Black to recapture with the f-pawn on g6, which is a positional disaster! } ) 
6. Qb3 { The most common move. White wants to see if we prefer to put our queen on b6 or c7. } Nbd7!? { A very interesting idea, played by the creative Hungarian GM Berkes. Of course, if we don't need to defend b7 immediately, we really shouldn't! This is based on a few tactical tricks due to the white knights being misplaced. } 
7. Qxb7 { The first question we need to ask ourselves is, of course: what happens if White takes the pawn? But this is simply way too dangerous, as White is now seriously lagging in development. } e5! 
8. e3 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { A key idea to the concept. White is not ready for this. A crucial point is that } 8.Qxc6 exd4 { is just fantastic for us, as White can’t really play e3 to finish development. We'll just follow up with ...Bc5 and ...O-O with a huge attack. } ) { The most solid move, but we still get a huge initiative. } exd4 { Opening up in front of White's king. } 
9. exd4 Rb8 
10. Qxc6 Bb4 {[%cal Ge8g8]} { We castle and bring the rook to e8. White will have to give back a significant amount of material to get castled. } 
11. Be2 {[%cal Ge1g1]} { The only way, trying to get the king to safety. } Bxd2+ 
12. Bxd2 Rxb2 {[%csl Rd2]} { Now White can’t castle due to the bishops hanging. } 
13. Rd1 O-O { Finally allowing White to castle, but we still have a couple of tricks up our sleeve! } 
14. O-O Bc2! { The start of a cunning and surprising tactical idea. } 
15. Rc1 Ne4! {[%csl Rh4,Rd2]} { Keeping the pressure up, hitting both the h4-knight and the d2-bishop. } 
16. Nf3 Nb6! {[%cal Rc2a4][%csl Rc6]} { Finally, our highly surprising tactical idea is revealed - the queen is trapped on c6! We threaten to pick it up with ...Ba4 next. } 
17. Ba5 {[%cal Ra5d8]} { Strictly, the only move to save the queen. } Qe7 {[%cal Rc2a4]} { Renewing the threat. } 
18. Bxb6 Rxb6 
19. Qxb6 { There is nothing better. } axb6 
20. Rxc2 Rc8 { White got a decent amount of material for the queen and therefore has drawing chances, but Black is certainly the only one that can play for the win here. } 
