[ECO "D11"]

1. d4 d5 
2. c4 c6 ( { The Slav! By playing the move ...c6, we support the d5-pawn, but the major difference to } 2...e6 { is that our light-squared bishop is not getting blocked in. Indeed, one of the main advantages of the Slav is that we rarely get bad pieces. Having played the Black side of the Queen's Gambit Declined and the Catalan, I have too many times experienced great suffering due to the c8-bishop never entering the game. That's one of the main reasons I was so happy incorporating the Slav in my Black Repertoire. } ) 
3. Nf3 ( { If White intends to develop both knights on moves 3 and 4, they usually start with } 3.Nf3 { but, from our perspective, it doesn't really matter, as we reply in the same way. } ) Nf6 { The most natural developing move. Now a lot depends on White's next move. If White is in an ambitious mood, they will try to prevent us from developing our light-squared bishop on the next move. If they are more solidly inclined, they allow it, and a slightly slower game emerges. } 
4. Nbd2 { This is a fairly serious move I have employed myself a couple of times. It looks strange to block the c1-bishop, but White intends to play it similar to the Slow Slav, [/course/140404/6] where the c1-bishop doesn't get developed anyway. } Bf5 { The most natural move. Play tends to be similar to the Slow Slav, but there are a couple of important differences we should be aware of. } 
5. Nh4 { Just as in the Slow Slav, trying to win the bishop is the only attempt [/variation/22637665/#/6/w] to show any ambition at all. } Be4 ( 5...Bg6 { This is not that relevant to us, as we anyway always prefer to flick in ...Be4 to provoke f3, but I still can't resist showing this gorgeous trap that I think is one of the main reasons 4.Nbd2 is so popular for White at club levels. } 6.Qb3 Qb6?! 7.Qh3 { Suddenly, the mating threat will force Black to recapture with the f-pawn on g6, which is a positional disaster! } ) 
6. Qb3 { The most common move. White wants to see if we prefer to put our queen on b6 or c7. } Nbd7!? { A very interesting idea, played by the creative Hungarian GM Berkes. Of course, if we don't need to defend b7 immediately, we really shouldn't! This is based on a few tactical tricks due to the white knights being misplaced. } 
7. e3 {[%mdl 32768]} { The most solid and perhaps sober move, but it's definitely not enough to put any pressure on us. } Rb8 { This is rarely possible in the Slav, but it makes a lot of sense when it is. The queen can be kept on d8, eyeing the kingside, whereas the rook is aiming at the White queen. } 
8. Be2 e6 { Natural development. } 
9. O-O Bd6 { Sometimes we go to e7 instead, but here the queen might want to use the d8-h4 diagonal. Additionally, there are some tempting tactical possibilities here that we should keep a look out for! } 
10. f3 ( { This was played in the only game I could find from this position, Boros-Le, 2019. It looks natural but allows some interesting tactics! } 10.g3 h5! { is also rather dangerous for White. The h4-knight really invites us to push our kingside pawns down toward the white king, especially as the queen on b3 is beginning to look seriously offside. By the way, starting with } { 10...g5 with similar ideas is also very tempting. } ) Ng4! {[%cal Gd8h4][%csl Rh2]} { A nice tactical shot. White is too weak on the dark squares. } 
11. g3 ( 11.fxe4 Bxh2+ 12.Kh1 Qxh4 { looks insanely dangerous for White and is indeed probably just lost. } 13.Bxg4 Bc7+ 14.Bh3 dxe4 { As simple as it is effective. There is no rush, as the white king is eternally weak. Simply castle and begin pushing ...f5 and ...g5-...g4. } ) Nxh2! {[%csl Rg3,Rf1]} { Continuing the tactics! } 
12. fxe4 ( { The only move not to lose instantly. Of course, } 12.Kxh2 { runs into } 12...Qxh4+ { . } ) Nxf1 
13. Nxf1 { Defending g3. } dxe4 {[%cal Gh7h5,Gg7g5,Gh5h4]} { We have a rook and two pawns for the knight and bishop, which is some form of material equality. But the most important factor here is the vulnerability of the White king. We can even push our h- and g-pawns to open up even further. Meanwhile, we don't really have weaknesses of our own, and our own king is completely safe. } 
