1. d4 d5 
2. c4 c6 ( { The Slav! By playing the move ...c6, we support the d5-pawn, but the major difference to } 2...e6 { is that our light-squared bishop is not getting blocked in. Indeed, one of the main advantages of the Slav is that we rarely get bad pieces. Having played the Black side of the Queen's Gambit Declined and the Catalan, I have too many times experienced great suffering due to the c8-bishop never entering the game. That's one of the main reasons I was so happy incorporating the Slav in my Black Repertoire. } ) 
3. Nf3 ( { If White intends to develop both knights on moves 3 and 4, they usually start with } 3.Nf3 { but, from our perspective, it doesn't really matter, as we reply in the same way. } ) Nf6 { The most natural developing move. Now a lot depends on White's next move. If White is in an ambitious mood, they will try to prevent us from developing our light-squared bishop on the next move. If they are more solidly inclined, they allow it, and a slightly slower game emerges. } 
4. Qc2 {[%mdl 32768]} dxc4 
5. e4 { A gambit line, which in style is completely different from how the 4.Qb3/Qc2 lines are usually played. } ( 5.Qxc4 Bf5 { is covered here [/variation/22640978/#/5/b] via the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/pp2pppp/2p2n2/3p4/2PP4/5N2/PP2PPPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Qb3 dxc4 5.Qxc4 Bf5 move order. } ) b5 { As usual in the Slav, when given a chance, we try to keep our c4-pawn. } 
6. b3 { The main move. White immediately clarifies the pawn structure. } cxb3 { We don't really want to give up our extra pawn. } 
7. axb3 {[%cal Gb8a6,Ga6b4]} { A rather interesting position. We have a clear extra pawn, and White is neither able nor intending to win it back. Instead, they have the center, and our pieces are passive. It's the sort of position where, if we are not careful, we might get stuck in an unpleasant bind, never able to free our position.

However, there is one good thing for us here compared to many similar positions - we have an excellent square on b4 for our knight. Therefore, our main idea should be a well-timed ...Na6-...Nb4, ruining White's coordination. } e6 
8. Bd3 { This is the most straightforward way to develop. With the bishop on d3, we should not rush to castle, as that might run into the e5-push. } a5 {[%cal Gb8a6,Ga6b4,Ra1a6]} { Important! We want our knight on b4, but ...Na6 is not possible immediately due to Rxa6; therefore, we need to play ...a5 first. } 
9. O-O Na6! {[%cal Ga6b4]} { The key idea. We are often happy to give up the c6-pawn in order to activate our position. } 
10. Bd2 Nb4 { We have transposed to this line. [/variation/22640977/#/10/b] } 
