However, there is one good thing for us here compared to many similar positions - we have an excellent square on b4 for our knight. Therefore, our main idea should be a well-timed ...Na6-...Nb4, ruining White's coordination. } e6 
8. Bd2 {[%mdl 32768]} { The most common move in practice. White is trying to clamp down on our weak dark squares on the queenside and prevent ...Bb4+. } a5! {[%cal Gb8a6,Ga6b4,Ra1a6]} { Important. We don't let White play Ba5, but just as against 8.Bd3 [/variation/22640975/#/8/b] we prepare ...Na6 without allowing Rxa6. } 
9. Bd3 { The only move that really makes sense. } Na6! { Important and strong! Again we are happy to give back the c6-pawn to win the bishop pair and free our position. } 
10. O-O ( 10.Bxa5?? Nb4! { wins material immediately. } ) Nb4 { Winning the bishop pair. We are actually ready to give back not only one but two pawns in order to get maximum activity. } 
11. Bxb4 Bxb4 
12. Ne5 ( { The best move. White is picking up the c6-pawn with the knight instead of the queen. } 12.Qxc6+ { is really quite dubious for White, as our bishops are very strong, and the center is now more likely to get weak than strong. } 12...Bd7 13.Qc2 O-O { Followed by ...Qb6, ...Rfc8, etc. As soon as the knight leaves b1, we get access to the c3-square. } ) Bb7 
13. Nxc6 Bxc6 { This might look a bit weird, giving up the bishop pair, the right to castle, and losing the b5-pawn. But as Dr. Tarrasch wrote over 100 years ago: 'The important thing is not what leaves the board, but what remains!' Here, what will remain is the knight terribly misplaced on b1, the weak d4-pawn and very active pieces for us. } 
14. Qxc6+ Ke7 {[%csl Rb1,Rd4]} { The king is not vulnerable on e7 at all, as White is too passive to create any threats. Meanwhile, d4 is hanging, but the most important factor is the b1-knight not getting out, giving us great compensation for the pawn. } 
