13. Nxe5 Qxe5 {[%cal Ge3e4,Yf2f4,Gf5g4,Ge7c5][%csl Gc6,Gb7,Ga7]} { An interesting structure. We do have a rather potent 3 vs 2 on the queenside, but by far, the most important thing currently is whether White will be able to push e4 and f4 in a good way. If we get pushed back, we might quickly end up on the receiving end of a big attack, but here our idea is to use the activity of our pieces to either trade them off (making White's pawn push much less dangerous) or get them active on the squares White weakens. In general, care is needed from us, but White definitely also risks overpushing. } 
14. e4 { The only real plan available to White. } Bg4 { Always a useful move, forcing a concession from White. } 
15. f3 Be6 { When White has a solid grip on the e4-pawn, we very rarely want to go to h5 with the bishop, as it easily gets offside on h5/g6. Instead, we now try to use the c4-square, should White be careless. } 
16. Be3 Bc5 { Just in time, trading enough pieces to make the f4-push less scary. } 
17. Rfd1 ( 17.f4 Bxe3+ 18.Qxe3 Ng4! { is another typical tactical resource which gives us the initiative. } ) Rfd8 { One of many possible moves. We are trading enough pieces for White's pawn push to be no longer scary. One day we will start to push our queenside pawns, but for the time being, activating our pieces and fighting for the d-file is our main agenda. } 
