4. Bg5 { A typical 'SOS' line that is still popular at most levels. The idea is to wait for a knight to emerge on f6 and then take it as quickly as possible. } f6 { A principled reaction, immediately starting concrete play. Now the game will no longer resemble an Exchange Slav but rather something completely independent. Slower ways of playing are also possible, but this seems to work out fine. } ( 4...Qb6 { is another decent line, but to my eyes, the lines after } ) ( 4...f6 { are a bit more logical and reliable. This is certainly just a matter of taste, though. } ) 
5. Bd2 { A funny-looking move, but actually the most interesting, by far. } e5 { I believe the most straightforward way is also the most convincing. We immediately force the issue in the center. } 
6. e4 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { Again, funny-looking, and again, the most interesting move! } 6.e3 { is timid, and hardly a concern for us. } 6...Nc6 7.Nc3 Be6 { With our solid center, we can't have any problems whatsoever. } ) dxe4 {[%cal Rg1f3]} { The right pawn to take, as now our e4-pawn prevents Nf3. } 
7. dxe5 Nc6 ( { Again, it's important not to fall for } 7...fxe5?? 8.Qh5+ { . } ) 
8. Nc3 ( 8.exf6 { would only help us develop. } 8...Nxf6 { intending ...Bc5 is just great for us. } ) fxe5 { Accepting an isolated pawn on e5, but we will get active piece play as compensation. } 
9. Bc4 ( { By far, the most common and scariest move. The bishop prevents us from castling, and we need to be aware of how to handle this. } 9.Nxe4 Nf6 { is no issue for us, as our pieces are getting very active. } ) Nf6 
10. Nge2 { This position has been reached a fair amount of times. We are currently a pawn up, but e4 is likely to drop sooner or later. } Na5 { I believe this is the most reliable continuation. We immediately get rid of the annoying bishop, making castling possible later. Additionally, the c4-square will become available for our knight after the bishop trade. } 
11. Bb5+ Bd7 
12. O-O { This was played, in the only game I could find in this position, by the strong GM Hakobyan in 2022. } Bxb5 { The simplest continuation. } 
13. Nxb5 a6 { Forcing White back. } 
14. Nbc3 Nc4 {[%cal Gd8d1,Ye4e3]} ( { So far, we have followed the game, but here instead of the reasonable } 14...Bc5 { , which eventually led to a draw, I suggest a slightly more concrete alternative. } ) { Forcing the trade of queens, after which we have nothing to worry about at all. Later, we can even flick in ...e3!? if we want to, in order to also ruin White's structure. } 
