1. d4 d5 
2. c4 c6 ( { The Slav! By playing the move ...c6, we support the d5-pawn, but the major difference to } 2...e6 { is that our light-squared bishop is not getting blocked in. Indeed, one of the main advantages of the Slav is that we rarely get bad pieces. Having played the Black side of the Queen's Gambit Declined and the Catalan, I have too many times experienced great suffering due to the c8-bishop never entering the game. That's one of the main reasons I was so happy incorporating the Slav in my Black Repertoire. } ) 
3. cxd5 cxd5 { The Exchange Slav is one of White's most solid ways of facing the Slav. With the pawn structure in the center more static, it simply becomes more challenging to create imbalances.

However, we should not forget that there are still 30 pieces on the board, which means there are plenty of possibilities for both sides. As Black, one has to make an important choice of how ambitious and provocative one wants to play.

Finally, after much consideration, I decided to recommend what I believe to be the most solid and simple way of handling the Exchange Slav. The downside of my proposed repertoire is that it could, at times, become a little bit dry. } 
4. Nc3 { It is important to pay very close attention to White's possible move orders. There are many natural moves like Nc3, Nf3, Bf4, e3, and so on, but the order in which they are played makes some difference.

However, one of the main advantages of the system I recommend is that we are hard to trick move order-wise. We can usually play the same moves no matter what White does. } Nf6 
5. Bf4 {[%mdl 32768]} { By far, the mainline. By delaying Nf3, White makes it a bit trickier for us to develop our light-squared bishop. } Nc6 
6. e3 ( 6.Nf3 a6 { transposes here. [/variation/22642539/#/6/b] } ) a6 { Again, I recommend the multi-purpose move ...a6. It stops Bb5, but, more importantly, it prepares the development of our light-squared bishop. As soon as the bishop develops, Qb3 is an important reply. With the pawn already on a6, we can safely meet it by ...Na5 Qa4+ b5. } 
7. Rc1 { This is a kind of counter-waiting move, but although the rook gets to the only open file, it's not the most useful move - we can now develop harmoniously. } Bf5 { Again we move to f5 instead of g4, and again I feel it requires an explanation. The reason is that without White having committed neither the g1-knight nor the bishop to d3, developing to g4 is rather risky. } ( 7...Bg4 8.f3 Bh5 9.g4 Bg6 10.h4! { With a bishop on d3, we would now just trade, but here the pawn push is rather unpleasant for our bishop. } ) 
8. Nf3 e6 
9. Qb3 { This is important. When we already have our pawn on e6, we must be more careful handling the queenside situation. } Bb4 { This is a good reply. This is actually a very famous position without the inclusion of Rc1 and ...a6, but somewhat surprisingly, it seems this inclusion favors Black. The rook is decent on c1, but normally Bb5 is the best move here, and now it is obviously out of the picture. } 
10. Be2 Ne4 { Forcing White to recapture with the pawn on c3, making the rook look rather useless on c1. } 
11. O-O Bxc3 { The knight on e4 is much stronger than our bishop, so we always give up the bishop on c3 instead. } 
12. bxc3 {[%csl Rc3]} b5 { Very typical play. } 
13. a4 { The only move. Otherwise, White risks ending up strategically worse due to the weak c3-pawn. } O-O! { A typical strategic idea. White can now win a pawn on the queenside, but it turns out that we get excellent compensation. This has largely to do with the fact that the bishop on f4 and especially the knight on f3 are out of play, as all action will revolve around the c-file, with the c3-pawn and the c4-square. } 
14. axb5 Na5 
15. Qb4 axb5 
16. Bxb5 { White picked up a pawn, but it's a risky pawn to take. } f6! {[%cal Gg7g5][%csl Rf4]} { A key move! We control the e5-square but also intend to push ...g5 next, making the f4-bishop feel rather uncomfortable. Furthermore, we prepare a hidden but strong idea. } 
17. h3 { The most natural move, saving the bishop. } g5 
18. Bh2 { Now the bishop is entirely out of play. } Rf7! {[%cal Gf7b7,Rb7b4]} { This is the hidden idea I previously mentioned. The rook suddenly switches to b7, after which White's constellation of Bb5 and Qb4 feels very vulnerable. }
19.-- ( { Actually, White has to play accurately not to collapse here - giving back a pawn by playing } 19.c4 { is the main survival idea. } )
