7. Be2 { The most topical move in modern top chess. White prevents ...Bg4 forcing our bishop to f5 instead. The downside is that e2 is not the most useful square for the bishop. } Bf5 { We are out of options, as the g4-square is covered. } 
8. Nf3 e6 
9. Qb3 {[%mdl 32768]} { By far the critical move, and the reason why 7.Be2 has been established as the mainline in recent years. The problem is that our standard reply, ...Na5 followed by b5, does not work here. } ( { Instead, the less forcing approach } 9.Ne5 Nxe5 10.Bxe5 Nd7 { allowed Black to eventually take over and win a nice game in Vallejo Pons-Andreikin. [/variation/22768398/#/9/w] } ) Nh5 {[%csl Rf4]} ( { This is extremely important. We force the bishop to either step away from the f4-b8 diagonal or block the knight's jump to e5. } 9...Na5? 10.Qa4+ { and now } 10...Nc6 11.Ne5 { is a disaster for Black, but @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1p3ppp/p3pn2/n2p1b2/Q2P1B2/2N1PN2/PP2BPPP/R3K2R b KQkq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@ 10...b5 11.Nxb5 axb5 12.Bxb5+ gives White a winning attack - here, we would need our bishop to be able to retreat to d7! } ) 
10. Qxb7 { This is a bit too greedy. White wins a pawn, but we get excellent compensation thanks to our bishop pair. } Na5 
11. Qc7 Nxf4 
12. Qxf4 ( 12.Qxd8+ Rxd8 13.exf4 Rb8 { gives us excellent compensation in the ending, as the doubled f-pawns cause the d4-pawn to be weaker. } ) Rb8 {[%cal Rb8b2]} { It's actually impossible for White to save the b2-pawn. } 
13. O-O Bd6 {[%csl Rf4]} { Useful to flick in, as the queen lacks good squares. } 
14. Qg5 Qxg5 { In general, being a pawn down, we don't want to trade queens. However, here all our pieces are so active that we risk nothing at all. } 
15. Nxg5 Rxb2 
16. Bxa6 Ke7 {[%cal Gh8b8][%csl Gd6,Gf5,Rg5,Rc3]} { Our bishops are strong, our rooks are active, and White lacks coordination, especially with the clumsy knights. At the very least, we will win back the a2-pawn with comfortable equality. } 
