Finally, after much consideration, I decided to recommend what I believe to be the most solid and simple way of handling the Exchange Slav. The downside of my proposed repertoire is that it could, at times, become a little bit dry. } 
4. Nc3 { It is important to pay very close attention to White's possible move orders. There are many natural moves like Nc3, Nf3, Bf4, e3, and so on, but the order in which they are played makes some difference.

However, one of the main advantages of the system I recommend is that we are hard to trick move order-wise. We can usually play the same moves no matter what White does. } Nf6 
5. Bf4 { By far, the mainline. By delaying Nf3, White makes it a bit trickier for us to develop our light-squared bishop. } Nc6 
6. e3 ( 6.Nf3 a6 { transposes here. [/variation/22642539/#/6/b] } ) a6 { Again, I recommend the multi-purpose move ...a6. It stops Bb5, but, more importantly, it prepares the development of our light-squared bishop. As soon as the bishop develops, Qb3 is an important reply. With the pawn already on a6, we can safely meet it by ...Na5 Qa4+ b5. } 
7. Be2 { The most topical move in modern top chess. White prevents ...Bg4 forcing our bishop to f5 instead. The downside is that e2 is not the most useful square for the bishop. } Bf5 { We are out of options, as the g4-square is covered. } 
8. Nf3 e6 
9. Qb3 { By far the critical move, and the reason why 7.Be2 has been established as the mainline in recent years. The problem is that our standard reply, ...Na5 followed by b5, does not work here. } ( { Instead, the less forcing approach } 9.Ne5 Nxe5 10.Bxe5 Nd7 { allowed Black to eventually take over and win a nice game in Vallejo Pons-Andreikin. [/variation/22768398/#/9/w] } ) Nh5 ( { This is extremely important. We force the bishop to either step away from the f4-b8 diagonal or block the knight's jump to e5. } 9...Na5? 10.Qa4+ { and now } 10...Nc6 11.Ne5 { is a disaster for Black, but @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1p3ppp/p3pn2/n2p1b2/Q2P1B2/2N1PN2/PP2BPPP/R3K2R b KQkq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@ 10...b5 11.Nxb5 axb5 12.Bxb5+ gives White a winning attack - here, we would need our bishop to be able to retreat to d7! } ) 
10. Be5 { The most obvious move, but not necessarily the most challenging. } f6!? { Let me say it immediately to avoid misunderstandings: this is dodgy! Although I haven't been able to find any clear advantage for White, my feeling is certainly that it is shaky for Black. However, the difference between shaky and bad is still rather big, and at least it leads to unusual and rather weird positions while seemingly avoiding all forced draws. Therefore, I include it as an alternative to 10...Na5. [/variation/22642561/#/10/b] }
11. Nh4! {[%mdl 32768]} ( { Now, after } 11.Bg3 Nxg3 12.hxg3 Bg6! { , we save the bishop pair and get what we want - a game with many pieces on the board and some imbalances. } 13.Qxb7?? Na5 { The big point of hunting down the f4-bishop. The queen no longer has access to the c7-square. } ) { The best move, but already not an easy move to pick among all the alternatives. } Bg6 { The only move. We can't let White ruin our structure. } 
12. Qxb7 { Similar to the previous line, but the inclusion of Nh4 Bg6 is favorable for White. } Na5 
13. Bc7 { Again, White's play is based on this rather weird move. } Nxb7 
14. Bxd8 Kxd8! {[%cal Gf8b4,Gb7d6,Yg6e8]} { With the bishop already on g6, we take with the king to free up the e8-square for the bishop (!). The knight will be well placed on d6 after we have developed our dark-squared bishop. } 
15. g4 ( 15.Nxg6 hxg6 16.g4 Nf4! { The same strategic idea works here as well. } 17.exf4 f5! { Followed by ...Bd6, likely picking up the f4-pawn. } ) Be8! { The point of taking with the king on d8. We save our bishop pair. } 
16. gxh5 g5 { Activating our position and forcing White back. The h5-pawn was unfortunately hard to attack anyway, so we don't mind trading it. } 
17. hxg6 hxg6 
18. Ng2 ( 18.Nf3 Nd6 { followed by ...g5 looks like decent compensation for the pawn. } ) Bb4 {[%cal Gd8e7,Gb7d6,Gg6g5,Ge8g6]} { Intending to finish development with ...Ke7 and ...Nd6. Later on, a useful plan could be ...g5 and ...Bg6 to activate the light-squared bishop and control the important b1-square. I believe it's a fairly reasonable position to play, especially in the sense of trying to win, but objectively, White should have a very minor edge due to the extra pawn.

Still, we should not forget White had to play a lot of good moves to reach here, making 10...f6 at least an interesting practical try. } 
