7. Be2 { The most topical move in modern top chess. White prevents ...Bg4 forcing our bishop to f5 instead. The downside is that e2 is not the most useful square for the bishop. } Bf5 { We are out of options, as the g4-square is covered. } 
8. Nf3 e6 
9. Qb3 { By far the critical move, and the reason why 7.Be2 has been established as the mainline in recent years. The problem is that our standard reply, ...Na5 followed by b5, does not work here. } ( { Instead, the less forcing approach } 9.Ne5 Nxe5 10.Bxe5 Nd7 { allowed Black to eventually take over and win a nice game in Vallejo Pons-Andreikin. [/variation/22768398/#/9/w] } ) Nh5 {[%csl Rf4]} ( { This is extremely important. We force the bishop to either step away from the f4-b8 diagonal or block the knight's jump to e5. } 9...Na5? 10.Qa4+ { and now } 10...Nc6 11.Ne5 { is a disaster for Black, but @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1p3ppp/p3pn2/n2p1b2/Q2P1B2/2N1PN2/PP2BPPP/R3K2R b KQkq - 0 10@@EndFEN@@ 10...b5 11.Nxb5 axb5 12.Bxb5+ gives White a winning attack - here, we would need our bishop to be able to retreat to d7! } ) 
10. Bg5 {[%mdl 32768]} { The most critical move, keeping the option of Ne5. } Qc7 { This is the other big point of 9...Nh5 - our queen gets access to the c7-square. } 
11. Rc1 { The other attempt to put pressure. } h6 { Kicking the bishop away. } 
12. Bh4 Bd6 
13. Ne5 ( { Again, necessary in order to put pressure. } 13.O-O g5 { wins the bishop pair. Although the bishops are not that much stronger than the knights here, this is enough to secure comfortable equality. } 14.Bg3 Nxg3 15.hxg3 O-O { Having the dark-squared bishop still on the board makes White's main plan of Na4-Nc5 less scary, meaning we are just fine. } ) Nf6 
14. Nxc6 bxc6! {[%cal Ga8b8,Rc7h2][%csl Rb2]} { Opening the c-file would be detrimental with the rook already on c1, but recapturing with the pawn is very decent. Our structure is worse, but we enjoy some strong counterplay along the b-file and the h2-c7 diagonal. } 
