In my previous course, 'The Magnus Queen's Gambit', I proposed a setup based on ...e6 and ...Bd6. While I still believe that setup is excellent, it clearly fits much better with the Queen's Gambit than with the Slav. } 
4. e3 { By far, the most common move. White keeps the c-pawn flexible, allowing both c4 in one move and Nc3 in some moments. } Nc6 { Continuing with our usual development scheme. } 
5. Nbd2 Bg4 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gf8e7,Ge8g8]} { This is our setup. The upside is developing the bishop outside the pawn chain so it will never get locked in. Also, the pin of the f3-knight makes c4 less tempting for White, as then we would have excellent pressure against the d4-pawn.

The big downside of ...Bg4 is that the bishop can easily get harassed by some combination of h3/g4/Nh4. However, from the Slav chapters, we got familiarized with the idea of giving it up for a knight already, so it should make us less nervous here. } 
6. c3 { The main move, and I believe what White will play automatically in 90% of the games. } e6 
7. Qa4 {[%mdl 32768]} { An interesting option, suggested by IndrekR in his Chessable course 'The London Attack: An Ambitious Repertoire.' Putting pressure along the a4-e8 diagonal is one of White's main ideas, and we need to treat it carefully. } Nd7 { A move also common in the Exchange Slav. [/course/140404/11] We prevent Ne5. } 
8. Ne5 { A concrete move, played a couple of times by the Austrian theoretician Felix Blohberger. White tries to put maximum pressure immediately. } Ndxe5 
9. Bxe5 f6 { Slightly annoying, but we need to play ...f6 at some point to develop the f8-bishop. } 
10. Bg3 cxd4 { Generally speaking, we prefer not to trade on d4, but here White was threatening dxc5 because our bishop would be hanging on g4. Additionally, we also have a concrete follow-up in mind. } 
11. exd4 h5! ( { Using the specifics of the position. We gain some space and time on the g3-bishop. } 11...Bd6? 12.Ba6! { is a very important trick to be aware of! We can't defend with ...Qd7, as the queen would be overloaded. } ) 
12. h3 Bf5 {[%cal Gh5h4,Gf8d6]} { Followed by ...h4 and finally ...Bd6. Our king can either castle or also be safe on f7. It's rather double-edged but looks fun enough. } 
