4. e3 { By far, the most common move. White keeps the c-pawn flexible, allowing both c4 in one move and Nc3 in some moments. } Nc6 { Continuing with our usual development scheme. } 
5. Nbd2 Bg4 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gf8e7,Ge8g8]} { This is our setup. The upside is developing the bishop outside the pawn chain so it will never get locked in. Also, the pin of the f3-knight makes c4 less tempting for White, as then we would have excellent pressure against the d4-pawn.

The big downside of ...Bg4 is that the bishop can easily get harassed by some combination of h3/g4/Nh4. However, from the Slav chapters, we got familiarized with the idea of giving it up for a knight already, so it should make us less nervous here. } 
6. c3 { The main move, and I believe what White will play automatically in 90% of the games. } e6 
7. Qa4 { An interesting option, suggested by IndrekR in his Chessable course 'The London Attack: An Ambitious Repertoire.' Putting pressure along the a4-e8 diagonal is one of White's main ideas, and we need to treat it carefully. } Nd7 { A move also common in the Exchange Slav. [/course/140404/11] We prevent Ne5. } 
8. Bb5 {[%mdl 32768]} { The most logical and most common move. } Rc8 {[%cal Ga7a6]} { Almost a novelty! Normally, Black plays solidly with ...Qc8, but I believe we can be ambitious here, sacrificing a pawn for tons of strategic compensation. } 
9. Bxc6 { The only challenging move. Otherwise, we would simply play ...a6 next, kicking White back. } Rxc6 
10. Qxa7 { IndrekR ends here without further comments, and indeed I believe many players will just consider this an extra pawn. But there are a couple of things working in our favor as well.

We have the bishop pair, and especially the light-squared bishop can become strong. Secondly, White has to lose more time retreating the queen. Thirdly, it's 'only' an a-pawn, the least valuable piece on the board. } Qc8 {[%cal Rc6a6]} 
11. Qa4 f6 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8,Yc6b6][%csl Gg4]} { I believe this move illustrates our concept rather well. We prevent Ne5, and make the f4-bishop feel slightly vulnerable to potential ...e5 or ...g5 pushes. But most importantly, we show that we are not in a rush. Our compensation is not of a temporary nature but rather long-term.

We can simply follow up with ...Be7, ...O-O, and then either play on the queenside with annoying moves like ...Rb6 or start some action on the kingside and center, perhaps someday preparing ...e5. } 
