9. Be2 { I imagine this is the kind of move one would often face when following this repertoire. White doesn't really bother with 'punishing' our setup but instead opts for natural development. } Be7 
10. dxc5 {[%mdl 32768]} { This was tried by Anish Giri in 2022. Normally, giving up the center voluntarily does not make too much sense, but here White has some concrete ideas. } Nd7 {[%cal Gd7c5,Rf3h4,Rg2g4][%csl Ge7]} { This looks like the most ambitious move. We prevent g4-Nh4, but also recapturing with the knight on c5 is very tempting. } ( 10...Bxc5 11.g4! { is White's point. } 11...Bg6 12.Nh4 { By trading on c5, White will be able to castle long later, as we don't have our ...cxd4 exd4 Nxd4-trick. Therefore, White could potentially get some initiative on the kingside. It's not bad for Black, but I believe it's a bit unnecessary to allow. } ) 
11. Bd6 { This must have been Giri's point. Else, we simply capture on c5. } Nxc5 ( { We can start with } 11...Bxf3 12.Bxf3 { . } ) 
12. Bxc5 Bxc5 { Normally I'd just say that we are very happy here, but White has some slightly surprising tactical ideas. } 
13. c4 { Hitting us on the light squares. } Bxf3 ( { Slightly surprising, but necessary for tactical reasons. } 13...dxc4 14.Qb5! { is the surprising tactical point! Suddenly, both our bishops are hanging along the 5th rank. We need to trade on f3, but then White gets active. } ) 
14. Bxf3 d4 { Hitting White on the dark squares - a very logical reaction after c4. } 
15. Qb5 Be7 { Unfortunately, this is necessary. There was no good way of keeping the bishop on the g1-a7 diagonal. } 
16. exd4 O-O {[%cal Rb4e1,Ge7b4][%csl Rd4]} { White has won a pawn, but the d4-pawn is hanging, and the king is not yet in safety. } 
17. Bxc6 ( 17.Nb3 a5! { followed by either ...Bb4+ or ...a4 gives us enough play for the pawn. White will either have to give back the pawn or get stuck in the center with the king. } ) bxc6 
18. Qa4 Rb8 {[%cal Rb8b2,Ge7b4,Gf8d8][%csl Rd4]} 
19.-- ( { The last key move. We threaten both ...Rxb2 and ...Bb4, and there is no good way for White to prevent both. A sample continuation is } 19.Qc2 Rd8 { One of many ways to get enough play. } 20.Nf3 Bf6 { White should give back the pawn in order to equalize. } 21.Rd1?! { Too greedy. } 21...c5! { Winning back the pawn anyway, due to the weakness of the b2-pawn. Now we are playing for an advantage! } )
