1. d4 d5 
2. Nc3 Nf6 
3. Bg5 { This is called the Veresov. A couple of years back, it had a brief surge in popularity, but basically, it doesn't make too much sense, and we have many decent ways of handling it. } Nbd7 ( 3...h6 { is also very decent, as it's a big concession for White to give up the bishop on f6. } ) 
4. f3 {[%mdl 32768]} { This is a very ambitious move, intending to take full control over the center with e4 next. The problem is that it weakens the dark squares too much and removes the f3-square for the knight. } c6 { An important move. We anticipate White's e4-break, and want to meet it with ...e5, immediately hitting on the dark squares. } 
5. e4 ( 5.Qd2 { Intending to castle long, but here we can utilize another point of the move ...c6. } 5...b5! { Immediately starting an attack! } 6.a3 { Necessary, but the inclusion of ...b5 a3 is definitely in our favour, as castling long now is a lot less attractive for White. } 6...h6 7.Bh4 e5 { would be the typical play, completely taking over the initiative. Next, we can simply develop and castle short. } ) dxe4 
6. fxe4 e5 { This is the point of our previous moves. White is likely to end up with an isolated pawn on e4, and importantly our knight will get an excellent square on e5. } 
7. dxe5 Qa5! {[%csl Rg5]} { A useful trick to be aware of. The bishop on g5 is vulnerable, and we securing the excellent e5-square for the knight. } 
8. exf6 ( 8.Bxf6 gxf6 9.e6 { was suggested in the forums, but it fails to impress. } 9...fxe6 { looks simple enough to me. We can always swing over our queen to the kingside if need be. The more creative } { 9...Ne5!? might be even stronger, but there is no real need. } ) Qxg5 
9. fxg7 Bxg7 {[%cal Gd7c5][%csl Gg7,Gc8,Re1]} { This is a dream scenario for us. White struggles to get the king into safety, and our two bishops will be fantastic. } 
