[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Classical Slav"]
[White "13) The Jobava London"]
[Black "Jobava London 3.Bf4 c5 4.e4 #1"]
[Date "2023.03.06"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/22642803"]
[ECO "D00"]

1. d4 d5 
2. Nc3 Nf6 
3. Bf4 {[%mdl 32768]} { The Jobava London! When Baadur Jobava started to play like this many years ago, people generally struggled to take it seriously. Normally, we are taught to not develop our knights in front of our pawns, but it has turned out to be quite venomous in practical play. } c5 ( { For this course, I have chosen a classical approach. In my previous course on the Magnus Queen's Gambit, I chose to recommend a system with ...Bf5. I still definitely believe this is a great system for Black, but in regards to the rest of our repertoire, and especially our setup against the London,  [/course/140404/12] I believe the mainline and classical approach with } 3...c5 { makes the most sense. } ) 
4. e4 { In interesting sideline, advocated by Hans Niemann in his LTR Jobava London course. I actually used to play quite a bit myself in blitz and rapid during 2016-2017, but my opinion has not really changed since then. It's a very decent surprise weapon, especially for shorter time controls, but if we are prepared against it, it's hardly a challenging line. } Nxe4 { Important. Trading a set of knights secures us much more freedom. } 
5. Bb5+ { When I used to play this line with White, I always gave this check. However, a couple of years later, I must admit it's nothing at all. } Nc6 { This is the only move, as otherwise, Nxd5 would crush us. } 
6. Nxe4 dxe4 
7. Ne2 { The only important thing here is to not cling on too desperately to the extra pawn. Instead, we should be ready to give it back to finish development. } e6 
8. O-O Bd7 { Not necessary, but solid and simple. White is likely to take on c5 soon, so we don't want to waste time with our f8-bishop yet. Next up, we can finish our development with White being unable to disturb us in the meantime. } 
*

