1. d4 d5 
2. Nc3 Nf6 
3. Bf4 { The Jobava London! When Baadur Jobava started to play like this many years ago, people generally struggled to take it seriously. Normally, we are taught to not develop our knights in front of our pawns, but it has turned out to be quite venomous in practical play. } c5 ( { For this course, I have chosen a classical approach. In my previous course on the Magnus Queen's Gambit, I chose to recommend a system with ...Bf5. I still definitely believe this is a great system for Black, but in regards to the rest of our repertoire, and especially our setup against the London,  [/course/140404/12] I believe the mainline and classical approach with } 3...c5 { makes the most sense. } ) 
4. e4 { In interesting sideline, advocated by Hans Niemann in his LTR Jobava London course. I actually used to play quite a bit myself in blitz and rapid during 2016-2017, but my opinion has not really changed since then. It's a very decent surprise weapon, especially for shorter time controls, but if we are prepared against it, it's hardly a challenging line. } Nxe4 { Important. Trading a set of knights secures us much more freedom. } 
5. Nxe4 dxe4 
6. dxc5 Nd7 {[%cal Rd7c5,Ge7e5]} ( { The most ambitious move! } 6...Qa5+ { followed by ...Qxc5 looks rather equal, but our move is aiming for a more complex fight. } ) 
7. Qd4 {[%mdl 32768]} { Clearly the most interesting move, and the one given by Niemann in his course. } e5! { The first tactical blow! Now play gets really sharp. } 
8. Qxe4 ( 8.Bxe5 Bxc5 9.Qxe4 Qe7 { followed by ...f6 is definitely not what White wants. } ) Bxc5 
9. O-O-O { This requires some care. The White king is vulnerable long term, but we have some concrete issues due to the d-file pin and not having castled yet. } Qh4! {[%cal Rf4g3,Gg2g3]} { Important, provoking g3 so White can't retreat the f4-bishop to a good square. } 
10. g3 Qe7 {[%cal Re5f4]} 
11. Be3 { Now there is much less pressure on our e5-pawn, giving us more freedom. } Nf6! { Superficially, this looks risky, as it allows an annoying check on b5, but it's important to act with force here before White can develop their kingside. } 
12. Bb5+ ( { The most challenging move. } 12.Qa4+ Bd7 { followed by ...O-O-O is perfectly fine for us. } ) Kf8! {[%cal Gg7g6,Gf8g7]} { Looks risky, but we have it all under control. It's all about the momentum here. Later on, the king will find safety on g7 after we play ...g6. } 
13. Bxc5 Qxc5 
14. Qc4 Qe7! { This is our deviation from Niemann's course. The trade of queens is obvious, but although Black is objectively fine, White has some initiative in the ending. Keeping the queens is much more challenging. We put our king on g7, and then we start our play along the c-file. To me, it looks like excellent counterplay. } 
15. Qe2! ( 15.Nf3 Bg4 { followed by ...e4 is a disaster for White. } ) g6 {[%cal Gf8g7,Gc8f5,Ga8c8]} { We are far away from the realms of the Slav, with an unusual position that might be a bit hard to grasp. In general, we want ...Kg7, ...Bf5, and a rook to c8. In the meantime, White will put pressure on our e5-pawn. We are happy to give it up in order to get our play going faster. All in all, it's sharp and very double-edged but certainly interesting to play. }
16.-- ( 16.Re1 e4 17.f3 a6!? { is an interesting way to get our play going. } 18.Bd3 { Utilizing the e-file pin. } 18...Be6! 19.Bxe4 Kg7 { Possibly followed by ...Bxa2!? next, but also just bringing the rooks to the center makes sense. White is struggling to activate the g1-knight, and the pawn deficit is not really felt at all. } )
