1. d4 d5 
2. Nc3 Nf6 
3. Bf4 { The Jobava London! When Baadur Jobava started to play like this many years ago, people generally struggled to take it seriously. Normally, we are taught to not develop our knights in front of our pawns, but it has turned out to be quite venomous in practical play. } c5 ( { For this course, I have chosen a classical approach. In my previous course on the Magnus Queen's Gambit, I chose to recommend a system with ...Bf5. I still definitely believe this is a great system for Black, but in regards to the rest of our repertoire, and especially our setup against the London,  [/course/140404/12] I believe the mainline and classical approach with } 3...c5 { makes the most sense. } ) 
4. e3 { The main move, and the way both Jobava and Carlsen play. } cxd4 { In the London System chapter, I talked [/variation/22642673/#/7/b] a lot about how we were not so keen on entering the Carlsbad structure. With the knight on c3, things are a bit different, however. First of all, the knight is misplaced on c3 in the Carlsbad, as White prefers their pawn to support the center. Secondly, if we don't trade on d4, White can consider dxc5!? which makes it harder to regain the pawn due to the knight on c3 available to protect it. } 
5. exd4 Bg4!? ( 5...a6 { is the traditional move, and a solid one as well. It looks to me like it equalizes without any big effort, but I still prefer } ) ( 5...Bg4 { for its surprise value and the fact that we immediately put a little bit more pressure on White. } ) 
6. f3 { The most common move. Our bishop does not have a great square to retreat to, but on the other hand, White can no longer play Nf3. } Bd7 { Necessary, to cover the b5-square. The bishop is slightly clumsy here, but the pawn also looks really ugly on f3. } 
7. g4 {[%mdl 32768]} { Played my Mamedyarov in 2022! But it should be noted that this was a rapid game, and I doubt he would have had the same success with it in a classical game... } Nc6 
8. Qd2 e6 
9. Bb5 { Another way of developing, but rather similar in style to our other lines. } Rc8 { Not strictly necessary but logical play by Harikrishna. } 
10. Nge2 a6 { Forcing the trade. } 
11. Bxc6 Bxc6 
12. h4 { And here, I again like the most normal developing move. } Be7 { We can still castle short if we want to next. As soon as White castles long, we play ...b5 with dangerous counterplay. } 
*

