1. d4 d5 
2. Nf3 Nf6 
3. e3 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { This is the starting point of the Colle System. In itself, it isn't such a bad system and has even gotten a recent burst of popularity, but similar to } 3.g3 { , White generally intends to transpose to the Slav if given the option. } ) c6 
4. b3 { This is the normal Colle setup, but it works much better if our bishop is blocked inside our pawn chain. } Bf5 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gf8d6,Ge8g8,Gb8d7]} ( 4...Bg4 { would work equally well. We have easy development, and White doesn't get the typical grip they are hoping for in the Colle. } ) 
5. Bb2 e6 
6. Bd3 Bd6!? ( { We are familiar with the idea of allowing doubled f-pawns from the Slav. } 6...Bg6 { would also be fine. In general, we keep our pawn on c6 instead of pushing ...c5 like Black often does in the Colle. Without ...c5, White struggles to open up for the b2-bishop, and it becomes difficult for them to come up with a good plan. } ) 
7. O-O O-O {[%cal Gf6e4,Gb8d7,Gd8e7]} { It's hard to predict exactly how the game will develop from here. There are rather few games, and it's all rather harmless, so I don't think we need to know any more concrete moves. Jumping with ...Ne4 makes sense next, and also just ...Nbd7, ...Qe7, and bringing the rooks towards the center. }
8.-- ( { The typical way to initiate kingside action in the Colle would be } 8.Ne5 Nbd7 9.f4 { , but here our bishop is fantastic on f5, rather than passive on c8/b7. } 9...Rc8 { Preparing the ...c5-push. The c-file will eventually get opened, so this is always a good square for the rook in these positions. } 10.Nd2 c5 { We have excellent counterplay. There is no reason to rush with ...cxd4 next, but rather we keep the tension and wait for White to show what they want. Just sitting on the e4-square makes sense, and one day we might even play ...b5!? utilizing the weakness of the c2-pawn. Again, everything would be completely different without our bishop on f5, making our king feel completely safe. } )
