3. c3 ( { The most serious of White's 3rd move alternatives. Both } 3.e3 { and } ) ( 3.g3 { are objectively more challenging moves, but only because White can still follow up with c4, transposing to other parts of our repertoire. } ) ( 3.c3 { was also recommended by Le Quang Liem in his LTR London repertoire, so we must take it seriously. } ) c6 ( { The most solid move. Objectively, } 3...c5 { might be the strongest move, but then we would be a full tempo down to our repertoire! We play } ) ( 3...c6 { to develop our light-squared bishop, after which the annoying move Qb3 can be safely met by ...Qb6. } ) ( 3...Bf5 4.Qb3 Qc8 { is what I played myself when facing 3.c3 in the last Olympiad. It also makes perfect sense. After } 5.c4 dxc4 6.Qxc4 { , play resembles a bit the 4.Qc2/4.Qb3 Slav, [/course/140404/10] but White has not yet committed to g3 while we have gotten ...Qc8 for free. My conclusion is that it's fully playable for Black, but 3...c6 looks even simpler. } ) 
4. Qc2 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { A funny-looking move, which 10 years ago I would just have laughed away. Nowadays, however, it has become increasingly difficult to fight for the advantage in the mainlines, so we see more and more creative sideline attempts, also by the world's very best. The idea of } 4.Qc2 { is to make it harder for us to develop our light-squared bishop. } ) Bg4 { Whenever possible, I like to get this bishop out. } 
5. Ne5 { This is the point of White's play. } Bh5 ( { The most normal reply. Strange moves like } 5...Be6 { are possible, but I believe there is nothing wrong with letting White execute their fancy idea. } ) 
6. Qf5 {[%cal Gf5h3]} { This is the only move that puts any sort of pressure on our position! It looks insane, but the queen intends to go to h3, after which our bishop on h5 becomes vulnerable. It has been tried by creative people like Jorden Van Foreest and is the recommendation of Le Quang Liem in his London course. } Bg6 ( { I believe this ties in well with the rest of our repertoire. We are okay with giving up our light-squared bishop for a knight to gain time and fight for the center. } 6...Nbd7 7.Qh3 Qc8! 8.Qh4 Nxe5 9.dxe5 Qg4 { becomes an incredible mess that looks okay for Black, but there is no reason at all to enter such concrete play with long lines. } ) 
7. Qh3 {[%cal Ge5g6]} Bxb1 { Forced, as White was threatening Nxg6. } 
8. Rxb1 e6 { So, we have once again given up the bishop pair. This time, we have a slight lead in development (or will get it soon) and, as usual, an incredibly solid structure. The knight has also gone to e5 a bit too early, making it easier for us to trade it off. } 
9. Bf4 { As usual, the problem with developing the dark-squared bishop is that it's likely to get traded off. } Nbd7 
10. e3 Nxe5 
11. Bxe5 Bd6 {[%cal Gd6e5,Ge5d6]} { Immediately trading bishops, after which we are just absolutely equal. } 
