1. d4 d5 
2. e4 {[%mdl 32768]} { The Blackmar-Diemer Gambit! To be honest, I think this gambit is one of the worst. Even something like the King's Gambit is much, much stronger. With many gambits, despite losing a pawn, there is some sort of concession from the opponent. Here I simply don't see our concession, apart from losing a few tempi. We still lack weaknesses, our king is safe, and we don't struggle to develop our pieces. There simply can't be anywhere near enough compensation for White. } dxe4 
3. Nc3 Nf6 
4. f3 { This is the point of the Blackmar-Diemer. White tries to develop fast and get some kind of attack going, but as mentioned, I simply don't believe in it. } exf3 ( 4...Bf5 { was my recommendation in the Magnus Queen's Gambit, and I still believe it's perfectly viable as well. Basically, against such a bad opening, there are many good options. } ) 
5. Nxf3 g6 { Actually important, from a practical sense. We rarely fianchetto our bishop in the Slav, but it makes a lot of sense here. The main point is to make our king more secure, and additionally, we keep the option of developing the c8-bishop later on. Also, we should not forget that it's allowed to go for counterplay, despite being a pawn up! } 
6. Bc4 { This is by far the most common move. White intends to castle short and use the semi-open f-file for an attack. } Bg7 
7. O-O O-O {[%cal Gb8c6,Gc8g4][%csl Rd4]} { The problem for White is that there are no weak points to attack. Actually, we can initiate pressure against the d4-pawn ourselves by playing ...Nc6 and ...Bg4. To me, it looks like Black is just clearly better. }
8.-- ( 8.Qe1 { is the most common move in practice. This is not theoretically relevant, but I just want to show one more idea for Black: } 8...Nc6 { Usually, this is a good square for the knight - if White pushes d5, the d-pawn becomes a target. } 9.Qh4 Bg4 { Putting additional pressure on d4, but also creating the possibility of eliminating the f3-knight, should it be needed. } 10.Be3 e6 { This is why I continued the line for a few extra moves. While not necessary, this is a nice way of stabilizing. The idea is to go ...Ne7-...Nf5, after which White will be pushed back. I am not sure if Black is objectively winning yet, but it's getting close. } )
