1. d4 d5 
2. Bg5 {[%mdl 32768]} { A strange move. Usually, the point of Bg5 is to capture the knight on f6, but here we don't have such a knight. Still, it's played from time to time as a way to get out of theory. } h6 ( { In my Magnus Queen's Gambit course, I recommended the more concrete response } 2...f6 { but, although I still believe that makes some sense, for a Slav repertoire it is logical just to play in Slav fashion, getting an improved version. } ) 
3. Bh4 c6 {[%cal Gd8b6][%csl Rb2,Rh4]} { This is slightly cunning. As usual, when the bishop leaves c1, the pawn on b2 could become a target. It also creates a surprising tactical opportunity. } 
4. e3 Qb6 { Attacking the pawn on b2, but also stepping out of the h4-d8 pin, making ...e6 possible later on. Additionally, there is another hidden resource. } 
5. Qc1 ( 5.b3 e5 { Again not necessary, but even stronger here. } 6.Nf3 exd4 { The simplest. } 7.exd4 Bg4 { Followed by ...Be7, with a comfortable position. } ) e5!? ( { Here is our extra option! This immediately solves all our problems, although, in some sense, they were already solved. } 5...Bf5 { is also possible, and we can also play our usual Slav moves with comfortable equality. It's really a matter of taste. } 6.c4 e6 7.Nc3 Be7 { is slightly precise, offering the trade of bishops. } 8.Bg3 Nf6 { Followed by ...O-O, ...Nbd7, and so on. There is nothing to worry about with our bishop outside the pawn chain. } ) 
6. Nf3 ( 6.dxe5?? Qb4+ { is the reason why we included ...h6! } ) exd4 ( 6...e4!? { is the more ambitious option, but I feel it somewhat plays into White's hands. Now we get an Exchange French type of position, but one in which White has burnt too much time with their dark-squared bishop. } ) 
7. exd4 Be7 { Offering a trade. This is admittedly rather dry but a simple way to equalize completely. } 
8. Bxe7 Nxe7 
9. Bd3 Bf5 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gb8d7]} { Trading our 'bad' bishop. It's clear that White can't hope for anything at all. If anything, we are slightly better as our queen is more active, but realistically it's closer to equal. } 
