18. Ne4 {[%mdl 32768]} { Castling on opposite sides usually leads to sharp dynamic play and this position is no exception. What is the most forceful way to get our play started? } h4! {[%csl Rg1]} { A very typical motif, very common in these lines. We are prepared to sacrifice quite a lot of material for our kingside attack. } 
19. Nxh4 Rxh4! { The point of the previous move. } 
20. gxh4 Ng4 
21. Ng3 ( 21.f4 { Possible, but insanely dangerous as well. } 21...f5 { One of many good moves, winning the c5-square. } 22.Ng5 Bc5+ 23.Kh1 Rh8 { With a very strong attack. The computers actually still hold the position together, but there is no doubt that practically Black is doing excellently. } ) Bc5 {[%cal Gc7g3,Rc5g1][%csl Rf2]} { Threatening ...Qxg3. } 
22. Ra3 { An imaginative and good defensive idea. } Bxa3 ( { The most straightforward move. Just continuing the attack with } 22...Rg8 { also makes sense. } ) 
23. bxa3 Ne3 { A nice tactical idea, ruining White's kingside defense. } 
24. fxe3 Qxg3 {[%cal Gd7e5][%csl Gb8,Rg1]} { Black is still technically a pawn down, but with a much safer king and active pieces, it's certainly a lot easier to play Black, despite engines again claiming 0.00. } 
