17... Be7 {[%mdl 32768]} 
18. { This time, we turn the board around and think from White's side. We are a pawn up, but Black has the bishop pair. How should we think in such a position? } Ne4! {[%csl Ge7,Gf5]} ( { This is an important and good move. White is really trying to trade off one of the strong bishops. } 18.e4? { was played in the game. The problem is that both the c3-knight and the g2-bishop are considerably worse now. } 18...Be6 { Black has fantastic compensation. The a5-pawn is a huge weakness, and the extra central pawns are not really moving forward here. } 19.Ne2 { Trying to reroute the knight, but it's slower than on the previous move. } 19...Bb3 20.Rd2 Bb4 21.Rd4 { The only move for White! The thing to realize here as White is that Black is the one with all long-term chances, so White must look for some very direct activity. } 21...Bxa5 22.Ra1! { Kicking the bishop out, after which Rb4 will be possible. Again, White is the one who should try to look for activity, and here they get at least some of it. } { Instead, the game went @@StartFEN@@r3k2r/1p5p/p1p2p2/P7/1b2PP2/1b6/1P1RNPBP/5RK1 w kq - 0 20@@EndFEN@@ 21.Nc3? and 21...Bxa5 would have been both simpler and stronger. Next up, Black can trade the rooks with ...Rd8, and the queenside majority will be the main factor. } ) Rd8 
19. Ng3! {[%csl Rf5]} { A good maneuver. The f5-square is the biggest weakness in Black's position. } Be6 
20. Be4! {[%cal Ge4f5,Gg3f5][%csl Ra5]} { Followed by either Bf5 or Nf5, this gives White decent counterplay. Most probably, the a5-pawn will have to be given up, but in the meantime, there will be counterplay in the center. } *

[Event "Lifetime Repertoires: Classical Slav"]
