7. Nxf5 exf5 
8. e3 Bb4 
9. Bxc4 O-O 
10. O-O Nbd7 
11. Qf3 {[%cal Rf2f3]} { In the theory section, [/variation/22637549/#/10/b] we discussed that White's main idea in this structure is to break open the center by playing f3 and e4. Therefore placing the queen on f3 is a bit dubious, as then White will lack a clear plan. } g6 
12. Bd2 Nb6 {[%cal Gb6d5]} { With the White pawn on f3, our counterplay is often based on the ...c5-push, which means the knight performs a useful task on d7. As White is playing slower, we don't want to open up with ...c5. Therefore, it makes a lot of sense to reroute the knight to d5 instead. } ( { Something like } 12...Re8 { also looks very reasonable. } ) 
13. Bb3 a5 {[%csl Gb4]} { A good strategic decision. Generally speaking, we should place our pawns on the opposite color of our bishop, but here we create a strong grip on the dark squares on the queenside. } 
14. Rad1 Re8 
15. Ne2 { A slightly odd move, but the knight wasn't doing very much on c3. } Ne4!? ( { Allowing White to keep the bishop pair. } 15...Bxd2 16.Rxd2 Ne4 { is similar and also very healthy } ) 
16. Bc1 { This feels a bit too optimistic for White. There is some long-term hope with the bishop pair, but all of Black's pieces are excellently placed, and the bishop isn't exactly great on c1 for the time being. } ( 16.Bxb4 axb4 { illustrates another advantage of our move ...a5 - the a4-pawn becomes weak! } ) Bd6 {[%cal Ge4g5]} 
17. g3 ( { Threatening } 17.-- { ...Ng5 . } { 16...Ng5! This surprising tactical idea is rather strong here. It turns out the White queen is lacking squares! 17.Qg3 Bd6 and now 18.Qh4?? Nf3+ wins the queen, but after @@StartFEN@@r2qr1k1/1p3p1p/1npb2p1/p4pn1/P2P4/1B2P1Q1/1P2NPPP/2BR1RK1 w - - 8 18@@EndFEN@@ 18.Nf4 Nd5 the queen on g3, combined with the knight on f4, looks shaky. } ) Nd5 { I think this position illustrates very well what we are aiming for as Black in this line. Our pieces are very well placed, and White is ages away from any pawn push and, therefore, from any plan.

However, White is still solid, and breaking through is not easy. With patience and good play, it's possible in the long run, though. } 
18. Qg2 {[%cal Gf2f3]} { Hinting at the possibility of playing f3 one day. } Qb6 {[%csl Rb3]} ( { I am not sure I'm such a big fan of the queen here, but it's a bit annoying for White with the loose bishop on b3. Still, something like } 18...Qd7 { strikes me as more natural. } ) 
19. Bc2 Nef6! {[%cal Rf2f3][%csl Re3]} ( { An instructive move! By preemptively stepping back from e4, Dubov eliminates all possibilities of pushing f3. Instead, } 19...Re7 20.f3 Nef6 21.e4 { would become very messy. } ) 
20. Nc3 Re7 { Now that White can't push f3, Black can slowly improve again. } 
21. Nb1 ( 21.Nxd5 cxd5! { is a good change of pawn structure. The d5-pawn can never really be attacked, and thanks to our active pieces, Black will be the one taking control over the c-file. } ) Rae8 
22. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2c4]} { This is a maneuver seen from time to time in this line and the Fianchetto Slav. [/course/140404/8] The knight is somewhat dominated on c3, so it prefers to go to c4 instead. } Qd8 
23. Nc4 Bc7 {[%csl Gc7]} { We rarely want to trade our remaining bishop for the white knight. } 
24. Bb1 { This looks odd, but the point is that White does not have any reasonable plan. Therefore, Yuffa decides to sit still and wait, but Black has a lot of improving moves available. } h5! {[%cal Gh5h4]} { Long term, the way we often break through in these positions is by pushing the h-pawn. If it gets to h4, the white king starts to feel vulnerable, but playing h4 is also a rather serious weakening for White. } 
25. Nd2 Kg7 ( { Dubov takes his time and improves slowly. Again, with full control, there is no reason to rush! } 25...h4 { is certainly possible immediately as well, and looks a bit more straightforward. } 26.Nf3 hxg3 27.hxg3 Kg7 { followed by entering on the h-file. } ) 
26. Nf3 Ne4 
27. Rd3 Bd6 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gd6e7,Gh5h4]} { Slightly improving the bishop. A later idea can be ...Re6 and ...Be7 in order to push ...h4. } 
28. Nd2 { This makes it a lot easier for Black. Continuing to just wait was unpleasant but necessary. } h4! { Of course! } 
29. Rb3 hxg3 
30. hxg3 Nxg3 { An effective way to break through. Black's attack is simply too strong. } 
31. fxg3 Rxe3 
32. Rxe3 ( { Desperation, but there was nothing better. } 32.Rf3 Re1+ 33.Rf1 R8e2 { wins immediately. } ) Nxe3 
33. Qf3 Nxf1 
34. Nxf1 { Materially speaking, White is almost okay, but Black still has a strong initiative. } Re1 
35. Qc3 Bb4 { There is no way to keep both bishops alive. } 
36. Qc4 Qd5 
37. Qc2 Qf3 { A great game by Dubov! } 
0-1

