1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} d5 
2. c4 c6 ( { The Slav! By playing the move ...c6, we support the d5-pawn, but the major difference to } 2...e6 { is that our light-squared bishop is not getting blocked in. Indeed, one of the main advantages of the Slav is that we rarely get bad pieces. Having played the Black side of the Queen's Gambit Declined and the Catalan, I have too many times experienced great suffering due to the c8-bishop never entering the game. That's one of the main reasons I was so happy incorporating the Slav in my Black Repertoire. } ) 
3. Nf3 ( { If White intends to develop both knights on moves 3 and 4, they usually start with } 3.Nf3 { but, from our perspective, it doesn't really matter, as we reply in the same way. } ) Nf6 { The most natural developing move. Now a lot depends on White's next move. If White is in an ambitious mood, they will try to prevent us from developing our light-squared bishop on the next move. If they are more solidly inclined, they allow it, and a slightly slower game emerges. } 
4. e3 Bf5 
5. Nc3 e6 
6. Nh4 Be4 
7. f3 Bg6 
8. Qb3 Qc7 
9. Bd2 a5 
10. cxd5 Nxd5 
11. Nxg6 hxg6 
12. g3 Nxc3 ( { It looks slightly weird to take on c3 immediately, but I guess Alsina Leal just wanted to make sure he got the structure in the game. } 12...Nd7 { is more normal. } ) 
13. bxc3 b5 { In the theory section, [/variation/22637686/#/12/b] we discussed this structure quite a bit. At first sight, giving White both the center and the bishop pair looks odd, but it's surprisingly difficult to create any real play as White, whereas all Black's moves are easy. } 
14. a4 ( { By far, the most natural initial reaction when reaching this position. White 'ruins' our structure and gets rid of the isolated a-pawn, but in fact, our passed a-pawn becomes more of a strength than a weakness. } 14.c4 { could perhaps be an argument for delaying the capture on c3. } 14...bxc4 15.Qxc4 Bd6 { followed by ...O-O still looks decent, though. } ) bxa4 
15. Qxa4 Be7?! ( { This is slightly inaccurate. } 15...Nd7 { also makes a lot of sense to kick the queen back with ...Nb6 as soon as possible. } 16.f4 Nb6 { In time, before White could attack c6. } ) 
16. f4 O-O 
17. Bg2 {[%csl Rc6]} { This is the problem with delaying ...Nd7-...Nb6. Now the c6-pawn is a bit of a target. } Ra7 ( { Stepping out of the dangerous long diagonal, but it all looks slightly artificial. } 17...Rc8 18.c4!? { is an interesting strategic idea. } 18...Nd7 19.c5! { Preventing ...Nb6. Now we can't get our usual kind of counterplay. } ) 
18. c4?! ( 18.Ke2! { This very accurate move would have led to a decent advantage for White. } 18...c5 19.Rhb1 { Activating the last piece and preparing Rb5 to put pressure on a5. } 19...Nd7 20.Qc6! { This is the point! As Black, we generally want to avoid the queen trade, as we lose both counterplay and control over the queenside. This would have been significantly better for White. } ) ( 18.O-O c5 19.Rfb1 Nd7 20.Qc6 { was also possible, but in the ending, the king is much more active on e2 than g1. } ) c5! { Now Black has excellent counterplay again. } 
19. d5 Bf6 
20. Rc1 e5 { It still might look like Black is under pressure, but Alsina Leal shows very nicely in the game how it is White who got to be careful here. } 
21. e4 ( { This feels dubious - there is no reason to weaken the dark squares further. } 21.O-O Nd7 { followed by ...Rb8 is similar to the game but in a better version for White. } ) Nd7 
22. O-O Rb8 { The start of a very imaginative and interesting idea. } 
23. Rb1 Rb4!? { A beautiful exchange sacrifice, in the spirit of Tigran Petrosian. White is forced to accept it; otherwise, the a-pawn starts marching. } ( 23...Rxb1 { For transparency's sake, we should note that also this less inspired continuation is completely fine for Black. } 24.Rxb1 exf4 25.gxf4 Bd4+ 26.Kh1 g5!? { Winning the e5-square for the knight also looks pleasant for Black. } ) 
24. Bxb4 cxb4 {[%cal Gd7c5][%csl Ga5,Gb4]} { For the exchange, Black has excellent control over the dark squares, a strong knight on c5, and most importantly, two very dangerous queenside passers. } 
25. f5 { Blocking the position even further feels wrong. } g5 
26. Rfd1 {[%cal Gd5d6]} { Intending to push d6, but it is easily stopped. } Be7 
27. c5 { I have a lot of sympathy for this move, trying to at least open some files for the rook, but Black is simply much better now. } Nxc5? ( 27...Bxc5+ 28.Kh1 Bd4 29.Rbc1 Qb8 { intending ...Nc5 and pushing the b-pawn is more or less just winning for Black. } ) 
28. Qe8+ { This is the issue. Now White gets some play. } Bf8 
29. d6 Qb6 
30. Kh1 { From here on, the game is just a mess and not that relevant to us. } Rd7 
31. Qxe5 Rxd6 
32. Rxd6 Qxd6 
33. Qxd6 Bxd6 
34. Rd1 Be7 
35. e5 a4 
36. Rc1 b3 
37. Rxc5 Bxc5 
38. Bd5 Kf8 
39. Kg2 f6 
40. exf6 gxf6 
41. Kf3 Ke7 
42. h4 g4+ 
43. Kxg4 Kd6 
44. Be6 Be3 
45. Kf3 Bh6 
46. Kg4 Kc5 
