17. dxe5 { Else, White gets a sad IQP. } Qxe5 {[%csl Ra4,Gb4]} { This is an interesting position to discuss in general terms. In the Slow Slav, [/course/140404/6] White often aims for this kind of position, with a slight but very long-term edge due to the bishop pair. Here, one big difference is that the pawn is on a4, giving us a grip on the dark squares as well as a target on a4. } 
18. g3 ( { Another common move from many similar positions, but here the bishop would stand better on f1 than a2. } 18.Rxd8 Rxd8 19.Rd1 { looks like a natural continuation to me, trading pieces to make the bishop pair stronger. } 19...Rxd1 20.Qxd1 Nfd7 { highlights the difference between this position and other similar ones. The knight will later go to c5, and the a4-pawn is weak. Just don't blunder the g6-pawn due to the pin, but start with ...Kf8 first! } ) Nbd7!? {[%cal Gd7e5][%csl Rf3]} { Interesting reactive chess. Caruana reroutes the knight towards the e5-square, as a new weakness has appeared on f3! } 
19. Qc2 { Slightly risky, stepping away from the kingside } Qh5! {[%cal Gd7e5,Ge5f3]} { Intending ...Ne5-...Nf3! } 
20. Bc4 Ne5 
21. Be2 Qh3!? {[%cal Ge5g4][%csl Rg1]} { Continuing to play for the attack. Now ...Ng4 is a threat. } ( 21...Nf3+ { already forces White to give up the bishop pair, but Caruana wants more! } 22.Bxf3 Qxf3 23.Qe2 Qxe2 24.Nxe2 Bxe1 25.Rxe1 Rd2 26.Rb1 { . These endings are slightly better for Black, again due to the queenside structure, but with the limited material, Caruana probably felt that the drawing margin was too big. } ) 
22. f3 g5! {[%cal Gg5g4][%csl Rf3]} { An important and very common idea to generate play. The doubled g-pawns are actually quite mobile, and pushing ...g5-...g4 is a great way to create tension around the white king. } 
23. Ne4 Qf5 ( 23...Nd5!? { was another good move, keeping more pieces on the board. White should probably have to play something like } 24.Bf2 { , but ...g4 will come sooner or later. After } { 24.Nxg5?! Qh6 , both g5 and e3 are hanging. } ) 
24. Bxb4 axb4 
25. Nxf6+ Qxf6 { This is another sort of position that often arises both here and in the Slow Slav. [/course/140404/6] Had the pawn still been on a5, I would say that Black has a pleasant edge, but after ...axb4, our structure is a little bit compromised, which means we have to be more careful than usual. On the other hand, the queen + knight combo is still strong, and the white king a long-term liability. } 
26. Kg2 Ng6 
