15. Nxg6 ( { Creating a very tiny imbalance. It's interesting to see how Kasimdzhanov uses it. } 15.Nc5 Nxc5 16.Rxc5 { is probably the driest way to play. } 16...Qd6 { . } ) hxg6 
16. f4 Qa5 {[%csl Gc4,Rc5]} { As usual, the critical factors in this position are the c-file and the squares on c4 and c5. } 
17. b3 Rac8 { I like how Kasimdzhanov handles this phase of the game. He is considerably higher rated, but he makes all the solid moves to first equalize completely and only then look for ways to take over. The main thing one needs to win such positions is patience. If we just keep on making good moves all the time, chances will appear. If we immediately panic and try something desperate, chances are good it will all backfire. } 
18. Nc5 Nxc5 
19. Rxc5 Qa3 { Now there is at least some very small tension on the queenside. } 
20. Rfc1 Ne7 { Again, Kasimdzhanov is not afraid of further trades. It's not that he is happy about them, but giving up the c-file would be much worse than just trading the rooks. Even with the limited remaining material, there is enough room to outplay a weaker opponent. } 
21. Qd2 Rxc5 
22. Rxc5 Rc8 
23. Qc2 Rc6 { Now it's a little bit risky for White to trade on c6, as the knight can later come to b4. } 
24. h3 Kf8 { Patience! There is no rush and no need to be drastic. First, bring the king, and then see how to make progress. } 
25. Kh2 Qb4!? ( { A cunning trap. } 25...Ke8 { also looked sensible. Once the king gets to d7, trading rooks will begin to make sense. } ) 
26. Rxc6 Nxc6 
27. Bxa6? { It looks like Black has blundered, but Kasimdzhanov has seen very deep. } g5! {[%csl Rd4,Re3]} { Surprisingly, there is no good way for White to hold onto the center any longer! } 
28. g3 ( 28.fxg5 Qd6+ { followed by ...bxa6 is the big tactical point. } ) gxf4 
29. exf4 {[%csl Rd4]} ( { The best try, but now d4 is lost. } 29.gxf4 g5! { works in the same way, but an even better version. Once the d4-pawn falls, the white position collapses. } ) Ke7 ( 29...g6 { is probably simpler, to hide the king on g7. } ) 
30. h4 g6 
31. Bd3 { ...Kd6 was coming, after which the bishop would have to move anyway. } Kf6 
32. Kh3 Qxd4 {[%csl Gd5,Rh3]} { It's clear that Black is better with the strong passed d-pawn and the knight + queen combo against the white king. It took quite a while to win, but in the end, Kasimdzhanov got there. } 
33. Bb5 Ne7 
34. Qc7 Nf5 
35. Be8 Nh6 
36. a4 Qd1 
37. Qe5+ Ke7 
38. Qg5+ Kxe8 
39. Qxh6 Qxb3 
40. Qh8+ Ke7 
41. f5 gxf5 
42. Qd4 Qc4 
43. Qb6 Qxa4 
44. Qxb7+ Kf8 
45. Qb8+ Kg7 
46. Qe5+ Kh7 
47. Qc7 Qg4+ 
48. Kg2 Qe4+ 
49. Kf2 Kg7 
50. Qd8 Qd4+ 
51. Kg2 Qg4 
52. Kf2 f4 
53. gxf4 Qxf4+ 
54. Ke2 Qf6 { And Barbot resigned. } 
0-1

