8. Nf3 e6 
9. Ne5 ( 9.Qb3 { is the critical move and we covered it in the theory section. [/variation/22642560/#/9/w] } ) Nxe5 
10. Bxe5 Nd7 
11. Bg3 Be7 
12. O-O O-O 
13. Rc1 Rc8 { A typical Exchange Slav. [/course/140404/11] Black has absolutely no problems, but it's interesting to see just how quickly Andreikin manages to take over against a world-class player like Vallejo. } 
14. Bd3 { Definitely a step in the wrong direction. The battle generally revolves around the c-file and especially the squares on c4 and c5. Therefore, the e2-bishop is actually more useful than the seemingly more active one on f5. } Bxd3 
15. Qxd3 Qa5! {[%cal Gc8c6,Gf8c8]} { Creating some pressure, but also preparing to simply double on the c-file. } 
16. Rc2 Rc6 
17. Rfc1 Rfc8 {[%cal Ge7b4,Gd7b6,Gb6c4][%csl Rg3]} { It looks solid for White, but actually, it's already rather unpleasant. Black has many easy moves like ...Bb4 and ...Nb6-...Nc4, and the g3-bishop looks slightly offside. } 
18. f3 {[%cal Ge3e4]} { Intending some counterplay with e4, but that also means additional weaknesses. } Bb4 
19. e4 Bxc3 { Simple chess, settling White with a weak c3-pawn. } 
20. bxc3 {[%csl Rc3]} ( 20.Rxc3 Qxa2 { simply wins a pawn. } ) Nb6 {[%cal Gb6c4]} { Activating the last piece. } 
21. h4 { White is trying to create some play on the kingside, but there are simply not enough pieces there to create any real threats. } Qa3 ( 21...Nc4 { threatening ...Na3 was another good option. } ) 
22. Be1 Nc4 
23. h5 h6 {[%cal Rh5h6]} { Definitely not allowing White to play h6, which would weaken our king considerably. } 
24. exd5 { Probably making it easier for Black, but it's hard to suggest good alternatives. } exd5 
25. Rb1 Re6! {[%cal Gc8e8]} { Switching to the open e-file. } 
26. Re2 Rce8 
27. Rxe6 Rxe6 
28. Bf2 b5 { The pressure continues. Black controls the entire queenside as well as the only open file. } 
29. Qc2 Qe7 {[%cal Ge7g5]} { A classy rerouting. } 
30. Kf1? {[%cal Re6e2]} { Covering the e2-square, but missing the other threat. } Na3 { And Black won easily. } 
